<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arena Players Ratify Contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The Arena Football League and its players have a
six-year labor agreement that includes a salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The league's Players Organizing Committee, the exclusive
collective bargaining representative of all AFL players, said
Monday the players voted to ratify the recently negotiated six-year
collective bargaining agreement by a vote of 6-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, AFL owners voted to ratify the agreement.
Previously, negotiations between owners and the players' union
lasted about five months. The players' voting process, which was
conducted by secret ballot, began during the last week of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement provides for generous salary increases,
accelerated free agency, and an unprecedented level of benefits to
our players,'' said Ronald J. Kurpiers, AFL deputy commissioner and
general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   AFL players have been working under an interim collective
bargaining agreement negotiated in March 2000. At the March
negotiating session, 34 AFL player representatives negotiated the
terms and conditions of employment for the 2000 season after the
league threatened to cancel the season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the new agreement:
</P>
<P>
   -- AFL owners agreed to pay approximately $1 million in
retroactive pay increases to all AFL players who played in the 2000
season and who are eligible. The retroactive pay will affect those
players who made less last season than the new minimum salaries
outlined in the six-year agreement.
</P>
<P>
   -- Any player with four or more years of AFL experience will
immediately become an unrestricted free agent, free to sign with
any AFL team once the new signing period opens this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   -- The AFL will operate under a salary cap, with an allowance for
player salary increases of up to 52 percent per year over the life
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   -- League owners will fund a players pension and retirement fund
through revenue sharing from the league's licensed merchandise
program. Revenues from the program will be split 50-50 between the
league and the union. Owners have agreed to pay $1 million into the
pension fund over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   -- AFL players will receive guaranteed increases in their minimum
base salaries. The new agreement requires first-year players a
minimum of $900 per game and a $200 win bonus; second-year players
are guaranteed a minimum of $1,250 per game and a $300 win bonus;
and players with three or more years of AFL experience are
guaranteed a minimum of $1,450 per game and a $400 win bonus. Any
player with three or more years of AFL experience may voluntarily
waive the minimum salary to fit within the team's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   -- A four-man practice squad will be instituted.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Murtha, who heads the AFLPOC, said, ''This agreement meets
the goals which the players set last year when they began their
efforts to form a union and bargain with ownership. The hard work
and sacrifice of our player committee has benefited all the players
of Arena Football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
