<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Add Wrestler to Olympic Team  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge on Monday ordered the U.S.
Olympic Committee to name wrestler Matt Lindland to the U.S. team
for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest reversal in a lengthy dispute that has
bounced between arbitrators and the courts since Lindland lost the
167&AMP;frac12;-pound Greco-Roman wrestling Olympic trials to Keith Sieracki
in June.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge B. Zagel ruled Monday that an arbitration
ruling that had led to a rematch -- in which Lindland beat Sieracki
-- should settle the matter. The arbitration ruling had been upheld
by an appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Zagel said a second arbitration hearing Thursday that was
decided in Sieracki's favor had not been confirmed by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Judges trump arbitrators when they have jurisdiction,'' said
Zagel, who stayed his order until 3 p.m. Tuesday to give the USOC
time to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   USOC attorney Irving B. Levinson said he would consult with the
committee. Meanwhile, Sieracki is trying to get an order from a
federal court in Colorado to uphold the arbitration that went his
way.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling goes back to the Olympic trials in June, when
Sieracki beat Lindland 2-1 on a referee's decision after overtime.
Lindland protested the match, saying Sieracki tripped him, in
violation of wrestling rules.
</P>
<P>
   After Lindland's protests were denied twice by USA Wrestling, he
appealed to an arbitrator, who ruled there should be a rematch.
Lindland beat Sieracki 8-0 Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Sieracki then filed his own appeal. But hours later, the 7th
Circuit decided that Lindland, not Sieracki, should get the Olympic
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys were girding for the possibility of more court action
in the tangled case.
</P>
<P>
   Sieracki, a military police sergeant, was rated as the top
wrestler for 2000-01 by Team USA and USA Wrestling. But Lindland, a
University of Nebraska coach who is working out with the U.S. team,
contends he should have been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The official deadline to submit rosters for next month's Olympic
games was Friday, but the USOC took the weekend to make a decision.
USOC attorney Levinson argued that, because of the deadline, the
question was now out of USOC's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland's attorney, Kevin B. Duff, said there was still plenty
of time to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Olympic Committee: www.usoc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 0033 </TRAILER>
