<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developer Makes Plea in Tax Charge  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Real estate developer Abe Hirschfeld pleaded no
contest to a state tax evasion charge on Monday and paid a $1
million fine with money he had set aside for bail in another case
on which he is serving a 1 to 3 year jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call from the jail in the New York Criminal Courts
building, the 81-year-old Hirschfeld crowed that the judge had
''dismissed the case'' and accused an assistant district attorney
of being ''a crooked lawyer'' who gave the court wrong figures.
</P>
<P>
   But Hirschfeld's lawyer, James Palumbo, said Criminal Court
Judge Bruce Allen had accepted an ''Alford plea,'' the New York
version of no contest, to end the tax case. Hirschfeld's health was
a factor in the decision, he said. Hirschfeld suffers from a
chronic renal ailment, gout and skin cancer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld was awaiting a second trial on the tax charge, his
first trial last year having ended in a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution claimed that Hirschfeld had evaded $5.5 million
in state taxes. Hirschfeld insisted he had paid all his taxes and
never received a bill for the contested amounts. Palumbo said the
state still may seek to recover the money in civil proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld was sentenced Aug. 1 to 1-to-3 years for
second-degree criminal solicitation, a charge stemming from his
attempt in 1997 to arrange the murder of Stanley Stahl, his real
estate partner of 40 years, over a business dispute, for $150,000.
Stahl died in 1999 of a stroke that his wife claimed was brought on
by stress over the death threat.
</P>
<P>
   Following his conviction on the solicitation charge, Hirschfeld
posted $1 million as bail but a court refused to grant his release,
a decision upheld on appeal last week. In Monday's ruling, Allen
allowed that money to be transferred to pay the fine on the tax
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told the court that I can afford it, the money means nothing
but my reputation means everything,'' Hirschfeld said in his phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   A flamboyant, eccentric figure who made millions in parking lots
and health clubs, Hirschfeld has run for several political offices
and once owned the New York Post for about a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 0042 </TRAILER>
