<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Husband sues hospital for wrongful death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Genesee Hospital has been sued for $1
million after an emergency room physician diagnosed a woman's
damaged aorta as muscular-skeletal pain.
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court jury in Rochester gave the award to Steven
Stewart, who sued the hospital for the wrongful death of his
30-year-old wife, Donna Stewart, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Stewart, of Walworth, Wayne County, was at a restaurant
with friends when she began having severe back pain, high blood
pressure and restlessness.
</P>
<P>
   She was taken by ambulance to the hospital, where a physician
suspected muscular-skeletal pain, ordered tests that showed
negative results, and discharged her after a sedative relieved some
of her pain.
</P>
<P>
   She died 10 minutes after her discharge when her aorta ruptured.
An autopsy revealed that her pain had been caused when her aorta, a
major artery that carries blood from the heart, began splitting.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors awarded $1,063,000 for her loss of income, household
services, parental guidance to the couple's two sons, and pain and
suffering, said the family's lawyer, David L. Murphy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
