<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Slip in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened slightly lower Tuesday as
investors locked in some profits amid thin trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 29.23 to 11,224.35.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 1.17 at 4,069.42. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 3.34 at 1,510.76.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have rallied in the past month as it became clear the
Federal Reserve is done -- for now -- raising interest rates to cool
down the economy and prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq on Monday gained about 28 points, to pull the
technology heavy index up for the first time since early spring.
The Dow, which gained about 60 point Monday, is now down about 2
percent from where it started the year.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancer by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 83.5 million shares,
down from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.45 to 526.93.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.23 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.44 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.19 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
