<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 30; Nasdaq Gains 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors ignored conflicting signs on the
economy Tuesday, as stocks opened mixed in thin trading.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 29.23 to 11,224.35.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was up 6.58 at 4,077.17. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 2.24 at 1,511.85.
</P>
<P>
   A new report showed Americans were less confident than expected
about the health of the economy in August, but remain optimistic
overall about its future prospects. The Conference Board said its
Consumer Confidence Index now stands at 141.1, down from a revised
143 in July and below its the 144.7 record level reached in May.
</P>
<P>
   But a separate government report showed that new housing sales
soared a surprising 14.7 percent in July, the biggest jump in seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors took profits Tuesday after a moderate rally
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have rallied in the past month as it became clear the
Federal Reserve is done -- at least for now -- raising interest rates
to cool down the economy and prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq on Monday gained about 28 points, to pull the
technology heavy index up for the first time since early spring.
The Dow, which gained about 60 point Monday, is now down about 2
percent from where it started the year.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancer by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 96.58 million shares,
up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.52 to 528.00.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.23 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.44 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.19 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.10 percent.
</P>
