<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Buddies Meet in 'The Crew'  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN WINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- On the front porch at a hotel for
senior citizens, four over-the-hill gangsters wear sour expressions
as they sit and watch the trendy traffic of South Beach pass by.
</P>
<P>
   The mobsters consider it a crime that they've grown old.
</P>
<P>
   ''You said the good times were going to last forever,'' Joey
''Bats'' Pistella grumbles to Bobby Bartellemeo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought we'd be dead by now,'' Bartellemeo replies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Crew,'' which opens in theaters nationwide Friday, is a
comedy about the aging wise guys rediscovering their zest for life.
If the plot sounds familiar, it's because another new buddy flick,
Clint Eastwood's ''Space Cowboys,'' is about four aging test pilots
rediscovering their zest for life.
</P>
<P>
   Do we have a Hollywood trend here?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a trend if it makes money,'' says Burt Reynolds, who
plays Joey ''Bats'' Pistella. ''If we were all dressed as flamingos
and it made money, we'd have 14 flamingo movies coming out next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ''These things come in bunches. I don't think it's a trend. It's
just a question of what the flavor of the month is.''
</P>
<P>
   But as baby boomers age, the potential market expands for movies
-- and books, songs and TV shows -- about the challenges of growing
old. The serious subject is also a fertile topic for dark comedy,
as ''The Crew'' proves.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Reynolds, the movie stars Richard Dreyfuss as
Bartellemeo, Dan Hedaya as Mike ''the Brick'' Donatelli, and
Seymour Cassel as Tony ''Mouth'' Donato. (The geriatric foursome in
''Space Cowboys'' consists of Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald
Sutherland and James Garner.)
</P>
<P>
   Bats has a heart condition, Bobby bad hearing and Mouth an
enlarged prostate, while the Brick has turned so soft that he
exchanges Christmas cards with other retired gangsters. None of the
four washed-up wise guys can bear to shoot even a corpse anymore.
Don Corleone they ain't.
</P>
<P>
   But when threatened with eviction from their hotel, they pull
off a caper that makes them feel young again, then sends them
unwittingly into a gang war with a Colombian drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
   The script is by Barry Fanaro, who wrote the TV series ''The
Golden Girls.'' ''The Crew'' touches on such issues as regret,
reconciliation and forgiveness, but never stays serious for long.
The pace is quick, the dialogue snappy, the characters sharply
drawn, and the result is a sort of Golden GoodFellas.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of the funniest scripts that I've ever read,''
Dreyfuss says.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Dinner, ''The Crew'' was shot on location,
with the superficial sheen of South Beach's beautiful people mined
for plenty of laughs. The film's stars -- Cassel, 65, Reynolds, 64,
Hedaya 60, and Dreyfuss, 52 -- couldn't help but feel old as they
sat on the hotel porch watching fashion models parade past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Occasionally some of them would look up and say, 'My mother
loves you!' Or even, 'My grandmother loves you!' But nobody was
throwing room keys at us,'' Reynolds complains before breaking into
his familiar cackle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were looking at each other, shaking our heads and saying,
'Isn't the view pretty, but we have nothing to do with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reynolds admits that while it's difficult for mobsters
and test pilots to grow old, actors actually have it pretty good.
They can keep working if they're willing to act their age.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very hard on actresses, but it's only tough for actors
who haven't had the courage to play old,'' Reynolds says. ''It's
all laid out there for you -- all those wonderful character parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedaya agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opportunities are there,'' he says. ''Look at Burt. He's
coming back like a dynamo. Unbelievable. He really pours himself
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, nominated for an Academy Award for his performance in
the 1997 movie ''Boogie Nights,'' is doing some of his best work at
an age when most people are ready to retire. But while he has
embraced roles of older characters, the former Florida State
football player still does his own stunts.
</P>
<P>
   In ''The Crew,'' Reynolds is physically thrown out of a
fast-food restaurant. A camera at ground level captures him in a
freeze frame just before he hits the ground face first.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence had to be shot 10 times, Reynolds says.
</P>
<P>
   ''You hear those dreaded words: 'Um, I had a little focus
problem,''' he says. ''It hurts a little more each time. What they
don't crunch the first time, they get the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should know better, but I thought it would make it a better
movie. I said, 'Just freeze-frame for a second, will you, so they
know it's me.'''
</P>
<P>
   In another memorable scene, as the four wise guys take advantage
of the early-bird special in a diner packed with senior citizens,
Reynolds' character rises from his seat and shouts, ''We would have
been better off dead!''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ''The Crew'' makes us believe otherwise, which could
be the start of a trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1139 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'The Crew'  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, four oldtime astronauts blast off from Cape Canaveral in
''Space Cowboys.'' Now four retired mobsters return to their old
tricks in ''The Crew.'' What's next -- Gregory Peck, Charlton Heston
and Jack Lemmon in ''The Three Grandfather Musketeers''?
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Watching old pros can be a pleasurable experience, and
even if they aren't as spry as in their heydays, their timing
remains impeccable.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Crew'' -- Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Seymour Cassel,
Dan Hedaya -- are really not as doddering as they are required to
play in this action comedy. They are first seen on the porch of the
Raj Mahal retirement hotel in South Beach, Miami, watching the
bikinis stroll by and reminiscing about the heists they enjoyed
when they were working for the mob.
</P>
<P>
   Their boring lives are disrupted when the hotel management moves
to evict them so the place can be upgraded to attract a better
clientele. Reynolds, known as Bats because of his weapon of choice
for quelling his enemies, devises a plan. Since Hedaya (The Brick)
works as a makeup artist in a mortuary, they would hijack a stiff
and make it appear that the man was a victim of a gang rubout in
front of the hotel. Hence the value of the joint would plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, they picked the wrong corpse. He happened to have
been the father of a Miami drug lord (Miguel Sandoval in a funny
portrayal), who dispatches his henchmen to track down the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Cassel is called Mouth because he rarely talks. But when he beds
a busty stripper, Jennifer Tilly, he tells her everything,
including details of the corpse caper. She threatens to squeal to
the drug lord unless the foursome perform a service: killing her
stepmother (Lainie Kazan).
</P>
<P>
   As if that isn't enough plot, police detective Carrie-Ann Moss
is working the case with a pushy old flame, Jeremy Piven. And it
just happens that Dreyfuss has been looking for a daughter he
hasn't seen in 30 years. Guess who interrogates him.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Dinner and writer Barry Fanaro both were
schooled in TV sitcoms, notably ''The Wonder Years.'' That
background is evident in ''The Crew.'' The action is speedy, the
wisecracks and sight gags flow with profusion. Some of the gags
just lie there, as though waiting for a laugh track. But the movie
speeds on at a breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   The four stars work wonderfully together in what is more farce
than comedy. Dreyfuss, the one note of sanity, carries the heaviest
load, and performs handily. A special nod to Lainie Kazan. When she
comes on the scene, the movie sparkles.
</P>
<P>
   For nostalgia buffs, the soundtrack is a winner. Two dozen old
platters, including ''Bim Bam,'' ''I Don't Need No Doctor'' and
''Too Hot to Stop,'' bring back the old sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Buena Vista release of a Touchstone Picture was produced by
Barry Sonnenfeld and Barry Josephson (they even put their portraits
in the opening credits, a first). Rated PG-13, for language,
vulgarity, adult material and violence. Running time: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
