<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 34; Nasdaq Gains 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Profit-taking left stock prices narrowly mixed
Tuesday, with bank and pharmaceutical stocks among the decliners.
</P>
<P>
   At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was
down 34.02 at 11,218.43.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was up 5.73 at 4,076.32. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.47 at 1,509.62.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are seeing a bit of profit taking,'' said Alan Ackerman,
senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ''There's also a lack of
volume, a lack of news, a lack of conviction and a lack of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Many traders were on vacation ahead of the long Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A new report showed Americans were less confident than expected
about the health of the economy in August, but remain optimistic
overall about its future prospects. The Conference Board said its
Consumer Confidence Index now stands at 141.1, down from a revised
143 in July and below its the 144.7 record level reached in May.
</P>
<P>
   But a government report showed new housing sales soared a
surprising 14.7 percent in July, the biggest jump in seven years,
indicating that consumers are upbeat enough to keep spending.
</P>
<P>
   Profit-taking brought financial services stocks lower, including
Citigroup, down $1.63 to $57.25 and American Express, down $1.63 at
$57.25.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, particularly those in financial services, have rallied
in the past month as it became clear the Federal Reserve is done --
for now -- raising interest rates to cool down the economy and
prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq on Monday gained about 28 points, to pull the
technology-dominated index into positive territory for the year for
the first time since spring. The Dow, which gained about 60 point
Monday, is now down about 2 percent from where it started the year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Pfizer and Johnson &AMP; Johnson fell after studies showed
their blood pressure and blood clotting drugs did not work as well
as expected. Pfizer fell 22 cents to $42.75 while J&AMP;J fell $1.31
cents to $93.44.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! continued to falter, losing $1.36 to
$120.70.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 337.94 million
shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.50 at 527.98.
</P>
<P>
   ------
