<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Confirm Hike in Flight Delays  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Late arriving data from the Transportation
Department confirm what most Americans already knew: June was a
miserable month for flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   The department's Bureau of Transportation Statistics said air
carriers posted a 66.3 percent on-time arrival record in June, down
from both the 74.3 percent mark recorded in May and the 70.9
percent recorded in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The data confirm passengers complaints and an earlier Federal
Aviation Administration report.
</P>
<P>
   The flight delay report is normally part of the department's
monthly air travel consumer report, issued a few weeks ago. But the
delay statistics were not available from a new computer then and
were made public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, United Airlines had June's poorest on-time
performance in June. That airline, the nation's largest, had an
ongoing dispute with pilots at the time which has since been
settled.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the FAA has reported that there were fewer
delays caused by weather and air traffic control in July, and
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has convened a meeting of
airline executives to work together to improve performance.
</P>
<P>
   The best on-time performance in June, Tuesday's report said,
came from Northwest at 75.0 percent. That was followed by Delta,
73.7 percent; Continental, 73.1 percent; Southwest, 71.1 percent
and TWA, 66.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the nation's 10 largest airlines were American,
65.5 percent; Alaska, 65.5 percent; US Airways, 63.3 percent;
America West, 60.5 percent and United, 48.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Air travel consumer report:
http://www.dot.gov/airconsumer/atcr00.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
