<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3rd Body Found in Russian TV Fire  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The giant Moscow TV tower that was engulfed in a
26-hour fire is stable enough to be restored, officials said
Tuesday as the search for bodies ended with the death toll in the
blaze listed as three.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the State Committee on Construction, Anvar
Shamuzafarov, said Tuesday that about 25 percent of the 149 steel
cables that bind together the sections of the 1,771-foot Ostankino
Tower had been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Emergency Situations Minister Sergei Shoigu said
experts have inspected the structure for two days and concluded
that it is stable.
</P>
<P>
   Flames spread through the tower on Sunday and Monday, raising
concerns that some of the tower would fall or that it would have to
be torn down. Losing the tower, one of Moscow's most striking
sights, would have been a blow to the city's image.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was the latest catastrophe in a month that some media
have started calling ''Black August.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Recent Russian history has never known such a tragic month,''
the Moscow News weekly said. It recalled the 12 victims of a
bombing in an underground passage in the capital, the 118-member
crew that perished when the nuclear submarine Kursk sank in the
Barents Sea and the three killed in the TV tower.
</P>
<P>
   The third victim was identified Tuesday as Alexander Shepitsyn,
a plumber in the tower, a spokeswoman with the Emergency Situations
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear whether Shepitsyn had died in an
elevator that got stuck about halfway up the tower after the fire
broke out and then plunged to the ground. Two bodies from the
elevator were identified Monday -- a high-ranking fire official and
an elevator operator.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue efforts ended on Tuesday afternoon, the ITAR-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   The fire started in the tower's thin spire about 1,470 feet
above ground because of a short circuit, officials say. It spread
downward, cutting broadcasts to the capital and burning the
observation deck and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ITAR-Tass said much of the tower's inside was scorched and
damaged from smoke but that some equipment could be saved. Most of
the damage had been done to cables running up the tower's central
shaft, it reported.
</P>
<P>
   The tower's upper spire was tilting slightly because of the
fire, surveyors said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire cut most television service in Moscow and its
surroundings, although channels were still able to transmit
nationally in spite of the fire. President Vladimir Putin on Monday
ordered that broadcasts of the major channels in Moscow be resumed
within a week, but it was unclear whether that could be
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have proposed plans ranging from broadcasting from the
top of the main building at Moscow State University to attaching
transmitters to dirigibles.
</P>
<P>
   Independent NTV, one of Russia's main channels, resumed
broadcasting its news programs in Moscow within hours of the fire
by using the signal of a UHF channel owned by the same company that
holds NTV.
</P>
<P>
   The fire in Ostankino highlighted the decay of Russia's
infrastructure, which has been neglected because of dire funding
shortages for years. The tower, which was constructed in 1967 and
came to symbolize the Soviet Union's technological might, is the
world's second-tallest free standing structure, behind the CN tower
in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't simply a tower. ... It was the symbol of an epoch
that now, it seems, has passed for good,'' the Vremya MN daily
commented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
