<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tearful Exchange in German Scandal  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- A former treasurer of Helmut Kohl's party burst
into tears at a hearing Tuesday after a once-powerful Kohl protege
accused her of lying about a money handover under investigation in
the scandal entangling the ex-chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Brigitte Baumeister's testimony was a dramatic peak after months
of digging by a parliamentary investigating committee, but it only
deepened the mystery about allegations that Kohl's former Christian
Democratic government traded favors for donations.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of conflicting testimony by Baumeister and Wolfgang
Schaeuble, Kohl's successor as party leader who quit after being
implicated in the affair, also ensured fresh nationwide headlines
on the financing scandal the party has been battling all year.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was an alleged $45,000 donation by German-Canadian arms
industry lobbyist Karlheinz Schreiber in 1994, when Kohl was
chancellor and party leader. Schaeuble, then the Christian Democrat
leader in parliament, and Baumeister each say they received an
envelope with the money and gave it to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Tears welled in Baumeister's eyes after nearly four hours of
confrontation at the witness table with Schaeuble, who accused her
Tuesday of launching a smear campaign against him.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice breaking as she turned to Schaeuble, Baumeister said
the testimony had been an emotional strain. ''To talk of an
intrigue was the worst thing I could ever have experienced,'' she
added, dabbing her eyes with a tissue.
</P>
<P>
   She denied forging a plot against Schaeuble and hinted that she
had been pressured to change her account. ''I've been through a
valley of hell,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble remained distant, even when Baumeister addressed him
by his first name, saying she would have ''gone through thick and
thin'' for him in earlier years and was now disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is getting more and more abstruse,'' Schaeuble snapped at
one point.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers had called the latest hearings to examine whether
Schreiber's donation was part of efforts to get Kohl's government
to lobby for a defense project in Canada by a subsidiary of a
German company, Thyssen.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of parliament's inquiry is a 1991 delivery of
Thyssen-Henschel tanks to Saudi Arabia during the Persian Gulf War.
German prosecutors charged Schreiber in March with bribery, tax
evasion and other counts related to money that allegedly flowed to
set up the deal. Schreiber is fighting extradition from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Baumeister testified Tuesday that Juergen Massmann, a former
Thyssen executive also charged in the Schreiber case, was present
at Schreiber's home when she received the envelope she believed to
contain a donation. But she said she only exchanged greetings with
Massmann and was sure the money wasn't from him.
</P>
<P>
   Massmann went before the committee Tuesday but refused to
testify, citing the pending judicial investigation. He even refused
to say whether he knew Baumeister, fanning suspicions of a cover-up
among committee members from the governing Social Democrats and
Greens.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both witnesses did not tell the full truth,'' said Friedhelm
Julius Beucher of the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble said he received the money from Schreiber and turned
it over to Baumeister to record as a donation. Baumeister says she
was handed the envelope by Schreiber after dinner at his Bavarian
home and later gave it to Schaeuble.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl set off the scandal last November by admitting he received
some $900,000 in off-the-books donations for the Christian
Democrats. He has refused to identify the donors, prompting
allegations that the money was in return for favors -- something
Kohl hotly denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1400 </TRAILER>
