<HEADLINE> Germany Has Budget Surplus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany will post a surprise budget surplus this
year, its first since 1989, the government forecast Tuesday, citing
both a record windfall from the sale of licenses to operate
high-speed mobile phone networks and the healthy recovery of
Europe's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   For the current year, the budget will show a surplus of 1.5
percent of gross domestic product, instead of a previously
projected deficit of 1 percent, the finance ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Figures were pushed into the black in part by the bidding of six
cellphone operators, which agreed earlier this month to pay the
government almost 100 billion marks ($46 billion) for the licenses
after a three-week auction.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrat-led government is banking on tight public
spending and a buoyant economy to help it balance the budget by
2006, though the finance ministry said it still expects to slip
back into deficit in 2001 when the one-time boost from the phone
auction falls away.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for a healthy economy improved Tuesday, after the
finance ministry said the economy grew 3.3 percent in the first six
months compared to the year-earlier period, the fastest first-half
pace since German reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, growth should now reach 3 percent, Finance
Minister Hans Eichel said after a meeting with his French
counterpart Laurent Fabius in the German town of Eltville. The
government had forecast growth of 2.75 percent as recently as May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
