<DOCNO> APW20000829.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Drug Flow Little Changed  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A decade ago in the same coastal city of
Cartagena, Colombia, that President Clinton visits Wednesday,
another American president hailed the creation of an ''anti-drug
cartel'' backed by $2.2 billion in U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   The summit with then-President Bush and three Latin American
presidents marked a milestone in international drug cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But a decade later, overall cocaine production in the Andean
region remains about the same, Colombia has become a leading
producer of heroin, and the price of cocaine on U.S. streets has
fallen with declining demand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Drugs have gotten cheaper and more plentiful, and the trade
has become more fragmented,'' said Raphael Perl, a narcotics expert
at the Congressional Research Service.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's brief visit to Cartagena follows the approval of the
latest U.S. anti-drug plan, a $1.3 billion package that Clinton
will discuss with Colombian President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they now have a unique opportunity
to crush the Colombian drug trade. But opponents are skeptical it
will keep drugs off U.S. streets, especially while America remains
the leading consumer of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Even some supporters of the aid package agree it won't be enough
by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a problem in the United States that we're not going to
solve in Colombia or Peru or Ecuador or elsewhere,'' said Thomas
McNamara, U.S. ambassador to Colombia at the time of Bush's visit.
''We're going to solve it here in the United States or we're not
going to solve it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Feb. 15, 1990, visit to Cartagena was as memorable for
security concerns as for its purpose. It was the heyday of drug
lord Pablo Escobar, who waged a war of terror in Colombia. Some
feared Bush would be a target.
</P>
<P>
   The trip passed without incident and Bush signed an agreement
with the presidents of Colombia, Peru and Bolivia to fight the flow
of drugs and to exchange information and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was successful in that it created an atmosphere of
cooperation on the drug front for the first time,'' said Bernard
Aronson, who accompanied Bush as assistant secretary of state for
Inter-American Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting helped strengthen regional economic ties. And
subsequent years produced victories: drug cartels were destroyed,
Escobar was killed and the cultivation of coca, the raw material
for cocaine, dropped sharply in Peru and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   But Colombia still poses problems. It remains the world's main
producer of cocaine and its coca cultivation has soared, from
92,700 acres in 1991 to 303,000 acres in 1999, the State Department
says. Moreover, Colombian traffickers are now major suppliers of
heroin to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Years of political instability have let the drug trade flourish.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994-98 presidency of Ernesto Samper was marked by political
chaos following revelations his campaign received $6 million from
the Cali drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
   And Pastrana's presidency has been beset by an economic crisis
and an intensification of a 36-year-old guerrilla war within
Colombia. Traffickers have been buying protection from both the
left-wing guerrillas and the right-wing paramilitaries vying with
them for territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration-pushed aid package is intended to
fight the narcotics and the instability.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our approach is both pro-peace and anti-drug,'' Clinton said
in a video address Tuesday to the Colombian people.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money will provide helicopters and other equipment
for two Colombian army anti-narcotics battalions, while about a
quarter of it is for social programs, such as helping displaced
Colombians and strengthening the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   The army battalions can clear guerrillas from coca fields so the
crops can be sprayed with herbicides. Land, air and river patrols
can prevent precursor chemicals -- essential to turning coca into
cocaine -- from entering the region and cocaine from leaving. And
U.S. officials believe they can work with neighboring countries to
prevent the drug trade from relocating.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also hope that attacking the drug trade will cut
funding for guerrillas, giving them more incentive to negotiate
peace.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents fear it will only drive the United States into
Colombia's civil war. They also object to helping an army with a
poor human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather than reducing coca cultivation and calming Colombia,
this is going to unleash Armageddon,'' said Bruce Bagley, a
University of Miami professor of international studies.
</P>
<P>
   He said coca cultivation will be pushed into other regions,
prompting clear-cutting of Amazon rain forest. More people will be
pushed out of their homes, some likely to join the guerrillas or
paramilitaries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rensselaer Lee, a consultant on international drug issues, said
traffickers have responded to pressures before by improving yield
and potency of coca crops, and they can do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''Traffickers are adaptable,'' he said. ''They are very smart
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Department on Colombia aid:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/colombia/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Center for International Policy, which opposes the aid:
http://www.ciponline.org/colombia/aid/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1651 </TRAILER>
