<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. May Discourage Russia Travel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States may discourage U.S. business
travel to Russia if Moscow does not allow an American jailed on
espionage charges to return home, State Department spokesman Philip
Reeker indicated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright would continue to raise the case of Edmund Pope with
President Vladimir Putin and other senior officials as they have in
the past until it is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''The treatment of Mr. Pope raises since his arrest by the
Russian government raises serious concerns about the safety and
security of American travelers in Russia and our ability to protect
the health and welfare of all American citizens,'' Reeker said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the State Department would issue an advisory warning
against travel to Russia, Reeker said, ''Obviously we have to
examine the implications of Russian action as this case is
prolonged.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was up to individuals to make their own decisions
about the countries to which they travel.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said Pope's wife, Cheryl saw him Tuesday for an hour and
a half accompanied by two U.S. consular officials. But he said Rep.
John Peterson, R-Pa., who accompanied Mrs. Pope to Moscow, was
denied permission to join the visit at Moscow's Lefortovo prison.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Federal Security Service arrested Pope April 3 for
allegedly buying plans for a high-tech submarine torpedo. Pope's
lawyer said he never intended to buy the secret plans.
</P>
<P>
   He faces 20 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has called for Pope's release, saying
Russian authorities have failed to provide evidence to support the
accusation. They have also requested specialized medical care.
Pope, 54, has a thyroid disease and previously was treated for bone
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a municipal judge rejected Pope's request for release
on bail for medical treatment despite a lawyer's argument that he
suffers headaches and dizziness in his jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   Pope, a former U.S. Navy intelligence officer, worked for Penn
State's Applied Research Laboratory after retiring from the Navy
and later founded CERF Technologies International, a company
specialized in studying foreign maritime equipment. He frequently
traveled to Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
