<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paramedics aid police commissioner's baby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Police Commissioner Bernard Kerik thanked
paramedics Tuesday for responding quickly to a 911 call his wife
made last week when their infant daughter was choking.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred last Friday evening, when Kerik was on his
way home from a dinner with First Deputy Commissioner Joseph Dunne
and Chief of Department Joseph Esposito.
</P>
<P>
   ''My wife contacted me, and was very distraught and upset,''
Kerik said. ''My daughter had been choking.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics from the Fire Department responded and tended to his
5&AMP;frac12;-month-old daughter, Celine, and his wife, Halah, he said. The
baby was taken to Columbia Presbyterian Hospital as a precaution,
but was released.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did a phenomenal job,'' Kerik added.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old commissioner said his daughter is teething and
had some saliva and mucus in her throat, and couldn't catch her
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very scary circumstance, to see your daughter choking,
so my wife called 911,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik got to his home in the Riverdale section of the Bronx when
the paramedics - Mark Donnelly and Michael Dealmeida - were still
there, but asked them to come to Police Headquarters for a formal
thank you.
</P>
<P>
   The 911 call was received at 10:35 p.m. A firetruck from Engine
52 responded in minutes, followed by the paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik has a 15-year-old son, Joseph, from a previous marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
