<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused carjacker of trooper's cruiser pleads innocent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) - A Union County man has pleaded innocent
to carjacking a State Police cruiser and another vehicle on the New
Jersey Turnpike during a snowstorm in January.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Montgomery, 30, of Hillside, entered his plea before
state Superior Court Judge John A. Sweeney on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held in the Burlington County Jail in lieu of
$100,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is accused of carjacking the cruiser of State Police
Sgt. Timothy Vanak on Jan. 25 in Chesterfield. Vanak had stopped to
help Montgomery, who he thought was a motorist stranded in the
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery sat in the back of the trooper's unmarked car while
Vanak called for a second trooper. When the second trooper arrived,
Vanak got out of the car, leaving Montgomery alone inside. Police
said Montgomery got behind the wheel and took off.
</P>
<P>
   Vanak scrambled into the back seat to try to stop him, but
Montgomery shoved a gun in the trooper's face, police said. The
trooper later jumped out of the moving car.
</P>
<P>
   The cruiser slid off the turnpike in Washington Township, Mercer
County, about 30 minutes later. Montgomery then carjacked a minivan
from two good Samaritans who had stopped to help him, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is charged with aggravated assault of a police
officer, two counts of carjacking, receiving stolen property,
weapons offenses and contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   State Police spokesman John Hagerty said the contempt of court
charge was filed because at the time of the carjacking, Montgomery
was wanted by the state Superior Court in Essex County for failing
to appear at a pretrial conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
