<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Interior Minister Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE GANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The quarter-century of Corsican separatist violence
that has stymied successive French governments led to the
resignation Tuesday of France's respected interior minister,
creating cracks in the left's governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre Chevenement, 61, who served three years as interior
minister, said his departure was the ''logical consequence'' of his
open disagreement with the Socialist-led government on a peace plan
for Corsica.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a three-decade friendship with Socialist Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, Chevenement said he could not defend the peace plan
before parliament in December. Daniel Vaillant, 51, Socialist
minister for parliamentary relations and a member of Jospin's inner
circle, was named to replace Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's peace plan would give the local Corsican assembly
limited legislative power. Chevenement fears that would fracture
France and encourage armed nationalists seeking more autonomy to
blackmail Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tomorrow, you could imagine a Basque parliament, a Breton
parliament. ... It's an attack on the definition of France,''
Chevenement said in an interview on evening television news.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time that Chevenement has resigned from a
ministerial post -- in character with the man who once said, ''A
minister shuts his mouth or resigns.'' His departure was a
cumbersome political development for Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Chevenement's Movement of Citizens was a critical element of
Jospin's so-called ''plural left'' that also includes Socialists,
Communists and Greens in the coalition government. Jospin has held
the coalition together since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents said Chevenement's departure was a sign the
left was weakening.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation ''is a failure for Lionel Jospin,'' said Michele
Alliot-Marie, the head of President Jaques Chirac's conservative
Rally for the Republic party. ''In his own camp, we see his closest
people ... denounce the ambiguities and risks of the accord ...
just as we have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Georges Sarre, a member of Chevenement's faction had a different
take. He said the minister's departure ''does not put into question
the participation of the Movement of Citizens in the plural left.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jospin appeared weakened. It was the second Cabinet
shuffle in five months, and Labor Minister Martine Aubry is
expected to go this fall to run for mayor of Lille.
</P>
<P>
   How to deal with violence in Corsica has been a burning issue
for the nine months since Jospin opened negotiations that led to a
peace plan. The plan, widely approved by Corsican lawmakers in
July, would give Corsica limited rights to pass its own laws
starting in 2004 if peace is restored.
</P>
<P>
   Corsican nationalist Jean-Guy Talamoni, who helped negotiate the
plan, said that with Chevenement's departure ''an obstacle has been
lifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevenement resigned from two other ministerial posts because of
policy disagreements. In 1983 he quit as industry minister, and in
1991 he resigned as defense minister, disapproving of France's role
in the multinational force in the Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
