<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven-alarm fire destroys four Wildwood stores but spares chapel  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) - An early morning fire destroyed four
Boardwalk stores Tuesday and caused an estimated $1 million in
damages. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-alarm fire, reported about 1:30 a.m., burned for more
than 12 hours, gutting an unoccupied two-story building at Baker
Avenue and the Boardwalk that housed two clothing stores, a T-shirt
shop and a dollar store.
</P>
<P>
   But it spared the Boardwalk Chapel, a storefront chapel located
immediately next door, where about 20 teen-agers from a youth group
were staying.
</P>
<P>
   The youths were awakened by a pizza shop owner who smelled smoke
coming from the adjacent building and knocked on the chapel doors.
They escaped unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The flames were about 20 feet up in the air, and there was
water coming from everywhere,'' said Kathy Poneleit, 37, of
Washington, D.C., who was awakened in her hotel by the smell of
smoke and walked to the fire. ''It was an amazing sight to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving firefighters attempted to extinguish the blaze on the
ground floor of the building, where much of the merchandise had
been stored, according to Fire Chief Connie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But the fire was fueled by plastic toys, stuffed animals and
other combustibles, and firefighters were driven back, he said.
After three attempts, they gave up and instead began attempting to
contain the fire, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At 3 a.m., we started praying for God's intervention,'' said
Elder Jon Stevenson, director of the Presbyterian chapel. ''God
uses many ways to carry out his purpose. This morning, it was the
firemen he chose to use.''
</P>
<P>
   The chapel sustained some smoke damage, and its white vinyl
siding was singed but was otherwise unscathed. Also untouched was
the construction site of a $70 million convention center being
built on the beach, about 50 yards from the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Blowing smoke enveloped the steel girders of the convention
center construction, but work continued unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 firefighters from four communities - Wildwood, North
Wildwood, Wildwood Crest and West Wildwood - battled the fire.
There was no reason to believe it was set, but the county fire
marshal and county prosecutor will investigate anyway, as a matter
of course, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just really stubborn,'' said Wildwood firefighter Aldo
Sacco. ''It wouldn't go out.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m., several firefighters remained at the scene, shooting
water from water cannons at hot spots in the building. The fire was
brought under control at 5 a.m. but wasn't extinguished entirely as
of late Tuesday afternoon, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   A 140-foot section of the Boardwalk itself sustained damage from
falling roof sections and the use of heavy firefighting equipment,
but it was minor, according to Alan Christenson, a public works
supervisor who inspected it.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the store where the fire apparently began said he
left work at 8:30 p.m. Monday, but that a manager worked until 1
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, whom he did not name, saw nothing amiss when he
left, according to Made in USA owner Neil Hamui.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the smoldering ruins of the store, standing in a
street flooded with water from the firefighting efforts, Hamui
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been here for five years, and then one day it all goes
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern half of the Boardwalk was reopened about 11 a.m. but
fire equipment and burned-out sections of building remained on the
other half.
</P>
<P>
   The fire occurred three days before the start of the Labor Day
weekend, the last fling of summer for vacationers and merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely bad timing,'' said Johnson. ''But the
Boardwalk will be open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1722 </TRAILER>
