<HEADLINE> Peru Denies Berenson Intervention  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The head of President Alberto Fujimori's
Cabinet denied Tuesday that the government intervened to overturn
Lori Berenson's life sentence and grant a civilian trial to the New
York native, convicted more than four years ago of terrorism by a
secret military court.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians have charged the surprise decision by the
military court on Monday was another example of government
manipulation in Peru's legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ''The presumption is that this came from government intervention
in the judiciary,'' Prime Minister Federico Salas told foreign
correspondents. ''In the case of Lori Berenson, nothing more was
done than confirm the actions of those within the country that have
powers over judicial affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The central government doesn't meddle in the military or
civilian courts,'' he said, adding that both he and Fujimori
remained opposed to the decision. Fujimori had still not commented
publicly on the military court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Council of Military Justice offered no explanation
Monday for why it voided Berenson's conviction and passed her case
to a civilian court.
</P>
<P>
   The former Massachusetts Institute of Technology student was
found guilty of treason in January 1996 for allegedly helping the
leftist Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement plan an attack on Peru's
Congress. Peruvian authorities say they foiled the alleged plan.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Clinton administration has urged Peru to grant
Berenson a new trial, arguing that the secret nature of her trial
didn't meet due process standards. Berenson and her supporters have
maintained that she was not allowed to present evidence at her
trial or to question prosecution witnesses before being sentenced
by a hooded judge.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has steadfastly sworn the 30-year-old would serve out
her life sentence in a Peruvian prison.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated that position in April during his re-election
campaign. He portrayed his presidential opponent, Alejandro Toledo,
as weak on terrorism for suggesting that Berenson's case might be
reviewed after a reform of Peru's judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a brutal campaign saying Toledo wants to liberate
the terrorists, that Toledo is a terrorist,'' Toledo said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said the Berenson decision was a dangerous move for a
weak court system that is vulnerable to government intervention and
private interests. He warned that without proper judicial reforms
in place, the move could pave the legal groundwork for the release
of other convicted leftist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson has denied that she helped mastermind the alleged plot
and insists she was never a member of the rebel group, commonly
known by its Spanish acronym, MRTA. But sympathy is not evident
from Peruvians, who were caught in the cross fire of rebel violence
during the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Burned into their memories is the image of Berenson's 1996
public pre-sentence declaration in which she angrily screamed
support for Peru's poor and shouted, ''There are no criminal
terrorists in the MRTA. It is a revolutionary movement.'' The
statement was considered by most here to be an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo also alleged the announcement of the new trial was ''a
smoke screen'' to divert Washington's attention from an arms
trafficking scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's military has been implicated in the purchase of
Russian-assault rifles from Jordan that were later diverted to
leftist Colombian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori claimed credit last week for busting the arms
trafficking ring, which he said included a low-ranking retired
Peruvian army officer. He and Peru's defense minister have denied
the armed forces had any direct role in the arms dealing.
</P>
<P>
   International pressure has mounted on Fujimori to improve Peru's
damaged democracy since he claimed victory in a May presidential
runoff, amid irregularities and allegations of fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1746 </TRAILER>
