<HEADLINE> Mexican Gov. Vetoes Abortion Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A law that would have made abortions for rape
victims a crime was vetoed on Tuesday by the Guanajuato state
governor after a nationwide furor.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Ramon Martin Huerta's veto was a setback for social
conservatives emboldened by their party's presidential victory last
month behind Vicente Fox and for Roman Catholic leaders who mounted
an unusually open campaign for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Guanajuato state legislature, dominated by members of Fox's
National Action Party, voted on Aug. 3 to tighten laws against
abortion by removing a clause that allowed it in cases of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates said the law promoted life and said rape victims who
had an abortion were not likely to be sent to prison. Abortion
rights groups said it added to the horror of rape victims.
</P>
<P>
   Huerta vetoed the measure after commissioning a public opinion
poll that showed most state residents opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   National Action legislator Miguel Cortes told the Guanajuato
newspaper Correo that the survey was based on ''lies and
falsehoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion is, with few exceptions, illegal in Mexico, and a move
to make the laws in one state even tighter turned the issue into an
unwelcome challenge for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who takes office Dec. 1 as the first president in 71 years
not from the Institutional Revolutionary Party, said during the
campaign that he opposed abortion but did not favor changing the
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The measure caused a furor among women's rights groups across
Mexico, who were already protesting a case in which a 13-year-old
girl was pressured to have her rapist's child in Baja California
state -- also governed by National Action.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's leftist Mayor responded by pushing through a law
here that allowed abortions in cases of danger to a woman's life or
of birth defects. Bishop Luis Reynoso Cervantes, the legal adviser
to the Mexican bishops' council, responded by calling the city's
mayor ''a murderer and a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that doctors who perform abortions would be
excommunicated.
</P>
<P>
   The open political activity by church leaders was dramatic in a
country that has sharply restricted the church's rights since the
mid-19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ''Guanajuato is not an isolated case,'' said Eduardo del
Castillo, spokesman for the Reproductive Rights Information Group
in Mexico City. ''It only revealed that there are ultra-rightist
groups that are attempting the absolute criminalization of
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said experts estimate there are 850,000 clandestine abortions
yearly in Mexico, and that as many as 1,500 women a year die of
bungled abortions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1747 </TRAILER>
