<DOCNO> APW20000829.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Woman Seeks Husband's Release  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID McHUGH
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The wife of a U.S. businessman jailed by Russian
authorities on espionage charges campaigned for his release Tuesday
in Moscow, saying he has done nothing wrong and was wasting away in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope said her husband, Edmund, appeared exhausted and
clung to her for a long time when she visited him Tuesday in
Lefortovo prison for the second time since his April 3 arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband looked weak and fragile and tired, and he didn't
look good at all,'' she said. ''He's concerned about his health.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Pope has a rare form of bone cancer, which was in
remission when he left for Russia in March, his family says.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Federal Security Service arrested Pope for allegedly
buying plans for a high-tech submarine torpedo. He faces 20 years
in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope and the Popes' representative in Congress, John
Peterson of Pennsylvania, said at a press conference that Russian
officials should transfer Pope to a hospital where he can be
examined by American doctors using up-to-date diagnostic equipment,
or at least allow a U.S. doctor to examine him in jail.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the security service has refused and a Moscow court has
upheld the refusal.
</P>
<P>
   Pope, 54, has reported headaches and dizziness that could mean
his cancer has returned, Peterson said. ''If Ed Pope does not get
quality medical care, he may die,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson and Cheryl Pope say the charges are groundless because
the information he was seeking was not secret. ''There's no basis
for the charges, no basis for any of it,'' she said. ''He was
invited and he was working with open technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope, a retired naval intelligence officer, runs CERF
Technologies International, a consulting firm in State College,
Pa., that developed commercial contacts with Russian organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope said her husband was sharing a cell with five other
inmates at Lefortovo. She said they sat on a couch and talked in
the presence of two Russian investigators and their interpreter.
Two U.S. diplomats also were present, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said Pope was seeking to acquire information on an
underwater propulsion system that was at least 10 years old and had
already been sold abroad through someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ed Pope is not a spy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The security service said in a statement last week that Pope was
using ''forms and methods of work that are completely in keeping
with the practice of military intelligence common in the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said efforts by the U.S. government to lobby for Pope's
freedom were being hampered because Russian authorities have not
revealed specifics of charges so they can be rebutted.
</P>
</TEXT>
