<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two dead loggerhead turtles wash up on shore beaches  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTNOR, N.J. (AP) - Two giant turtles washed up dead on New
Jersey beaches Tuesday, but authorities said the incidents were
unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   Both were 4-foot-long loggerhead turtles weighing more than 300
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The first was spotted on the beach here at Pittsburgh Avenue
early Tuesday morning, according to Sheila Dean, co-director of the
Marine Mammal Stranding Center in Brigantine.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what killed the turtle, which was already
decomposed when it was beached. For more than nine hours, the
turtle lay on the beach, with sunbathers and Boardwalk passers-by
gathering around it to gawk.
</P>
<P>
   The second turned up on a beach in Avalon. It had apparently
been hit by a boat. Propeller marks were visible on its shell, Dean
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such strandings are not unusual, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have them all the time. It's just something we get in the
late summer and early fall every year,'' said Dean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
