<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader makes Buffalo stop  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Green Party candidate Ralph Nader has been
called a spoiler in this year's presidential race, taking votes
away from Democrat Al Gore and giving Republican George W. Bush an
extra nudge in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, ''You can't spoil a system that's spoiled to
the core.'' Besides, Nader said during a campaign stop Tuesday,
''the outcome could be that Gore is taking votes away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first campaign stop in upstate New York's largest city by
any presidential candidate, Nader characterized the Democratic and
Republican parties as ''look-alike parties'' whose candidates are
indistinguishable on the major issues of the day: ''the really big
issues of democracy and the concentration of power and the denial
of labor and consumer rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ''On the issue of your tax dollars going to subsidize stadiums
and ball parks instead of rebuilding schools and public
transportation, the Republicans and Democrats are the same,'' Nader
added, touching a nerve here, where leaders have been tapped to
help out professional sports teams and the school buildings are the
oldest in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Green Party platform is the deepest, the broadest, the
fairest, the most farseeing, the most constructive political
platform in America today,'' he told about 200 supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Painting Gore as having ''surrendered to corporate polluters''
and Bush as ''the corporate welfare king,'' Nader said the
expectation level in the country is far lower than it should be
because big business has put the kibosh on things like adequate
paid maternity leave and vacations and universal health care -
things western European countries have had for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's our excuse? Big business controls this country,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed a universal health care system with public funding,
private delivery and controls against profiteering and malpractice,
similar to Canada's single-payer system.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged price restraints for drugs that are developed with
taxpayer dollars and then farmed out to pharmaceutical companies to
sell at huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of giving away a monopoly on these taxpayer-funded
drugs to just one company, multiple licenses should be issued to
any company that wants to sell them,'' he said. ''That would create
competition and bring down prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader saved his harshest words for the Democratic Party itself,
which he said has been too quick to blame the Republican-controlled
Congress for its shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ''How low must our expectations get, in terms of Washington
politics, before we blame adequately the Democratic Party for
allowing the right wing of the opposing Republican Party to gain
control of the Congress?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can't rely on the Democratic Party to save our
Legislature, our Congress, from the likes of Newt Gingrich and
Trent Lott, Tom Delay and Dick Armey - among the most craven, the
most evil members of the Congress in recent years - what good are
they?'' he said. ''What good are the Democrats?''
</P>
<P>
   A day after a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of likely voters showed
the consumer advocate at 3 percent, Nader was critical of a
decision by the Commission on Presidential Debates to exclude
candidates who draw less than 15 percent in national polls. Without
national debate exposure the poll results won't easily change,
Nader said, pointing to Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was at 8 percent in the polls of Minnesota until he got on
the debates,'' Nader said, ''and he got on 10 debates and he went
on to victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The least Nader is hoping for is 5 percent of the vote, the
threshold at which parties qualify for federal funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1759 </TRAILER>
