<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman wants health care, campaign finance on fall legislative agenda </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman wants to rewrite the
state's campaign finance laws, increase funding for health care
programs, help patients with HMO problems and fight home
improvement scam artists.
</P>
<P>
   And she says it can all be done this fall - if the Legislature
cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in her two terms, Whitman detailed her plans
for an upcoming legislative session during a meeting with reporters
invited to her office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to lay out what we need to get done now,''
Whitman said, adding that she's doing this now before the looming
governor's race draws attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are things I think we can get done this fall,'' Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman wants advocacy groups that campaign for or against
candidates to identify their donors. She wants the matching state
funds for out-of-state contributors to the governor's race
eliminated. Taxpayers donate two dollars for every one dollar
raised over a set threshold by candidates who raise enough private
funds to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   And Whitman wants these approved changes before election day
Nov. 7. That would force her potential successors to campaign by
her rules.
</P>
<P>
   Topping her list of reforms is the new disclosure laws.
</P>
<P>
   Groups often attack candidates but rarely make public who
finances their advertising campaign, Whitman said. Organizers
choose names that belie their agenda, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it really helps the public to know how much
credibility to give it if they know who's behind it,'' Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates have the right to raise money, but citizens deserve
to know where it comes from, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is good for the public to know who is contributing here,
but we have these loopholes,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey residents should expect to hear from national groups
promoting their specific agendas and candidates in the next
campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want the electorate to have as much information as they can
have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Specific legislation is not completed, Whitman said, but her
legal advisers say the proposals will withstand court challenges.
Many campaign finance reforms are said to infringe on
constitutional rights of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to hamper free speech,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's only proposals that had specific price tags attached
were her health care initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The governor would increase the number of people receiving
health care by raising the cutoff for the Family Care program.
</P>
<P>
   People who leave welfare for work programs earn more than the
federal poverty level of $8,000 - the current maximum for the
health insurance. Whitman said that should be increased to cover
people earning the minimum wage, about 130 percent of the federal
level.
</P>
<P>
   That would cost the state $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something I think we need to do,'' Whitman said.
''We're so focused on welfare to work and making it work. One of
the most important things we can do is remove barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislators will also be asked to approve increases in Medicaid
payments to doctors and in the Pharmaceutical Assistance to the
Aged and Disabled program. PAAD benefits provide state-subsidized
prescriptions for those over 65 and disabled people over 18 can
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still not providing everything we could for our
seniors,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The current budget includes $25 million for increases beginning
in January. The program would need $50 million for a full year.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also suggested a state panel to aid patients
through the ''cumbersome process'' of challenging HMO insurance
decisions. Disappointed patients should be able to sue the
insurance company, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another consumer protection proposal would target home
improvement contractors. If it becomes law, all contractors would
be registered with the state. Whitman would increase criminal
penalties for consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many of these people are fly by night,'' Whitman said.
''You have no way to get back at them because you don't know who
they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
