<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAfrica Leaders Get Into Racism Spat  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- It was supposed to be a
gathering of reconciliation, with South African civic leaders,
politicians and professors working to overcome the racial wounds
that continue to fester here six years after the fall of the racist
apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
   But the national conference on racism beginning Wednesday
threatens to be overshadowed by a nasty racial spat between
President Thabo Mbeki and the white leader of the opposition
Democratic Party, Tony Leon.
</P>
<P>
   In an ongoing media battle using Shakespeare allusions and
idioms from the American West, Mbeki has called Leon a racist
seeking to divide the country, while Leon has accused Mbeki of
using race as a weapon to bludgeon his critics.
</P>
<P>
   The argument came as a government minister criticized white
women for being apathetic to civic life in South Africa and the
country's Human Rights Commission issued a report calling the media
a racist institution dominated by minority whites.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be stupid and ignorant not to recognize that race and
racism is very real in South Africa, even now,'' said Sean Jacobs,
a political analyst with the Institute for Democracy in South
Africa. Racism is almost part of the national fabric, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Mbeki and Leon began with a little reported
speech Leon made last month, criticizing Mbeki's controversial
stance on fighting the AIDS pandemic in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has ''a near-obsession with finding 'African solutions' to
every problem -- even if this means flouting scientific facts about
AIDS in favor of snake-oil cures and quackery,'' Leon said.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki responded during a high-profile lecture Aug. 11, in which
he referred to Leon only as ''the white politician,'' and compared
him to Prospero in Shakespeare's ''The Tempest,'' who enslaves the
inhabitants of a foreign land.
</P>
<P>
   ''The white politician makes bold to speak openly of his disdain
and contempt for African solutions to the challenges that face the
people of our continent,'' he said. ''According to him ... these
solutions, because they are African, could not but consist of
pagan, savage, superstitious and unscientific responses typical of
the African people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon later said he was simply using innocent idioms from the
American Old West to refer to Virodene, an AIDS drug developed by
South Africa that was found to contain an industrial solvent, and
Mbeki's AIDS advisory panel, which includes controversial
scientists who have questioned the link between HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's response was ''sheer opportunism and vote seeking,''
Leon said Tuesday. The president was simply using race to distract
his voters from more serious issues in advance of local government
elections in November, Leon said.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki and Leon, however, were not actually talking to each
other, but to their very divided constituencies: Mbeki to the
mainly black African National Congress electorate and Leon to his
overwhelmingly white voters, Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Leon has asked that the exchange be discussed at the racism
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Barney Pityana, the head of the South African Human Rights
Commission, which is running the conference, has said the argument
is unlikely to affect the four days of speeches and workshops,
covering everything from the history of racism to reconciliation
and nation building.
</P>
<P>
   Pityana released a report last week criticizing the nation's
media as racist and suggesting that journalists receive sensitivity
training and news organizations create a code of conduct to punish
racist conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The report and the Leon-Mbeki disagreement came as many white
South Africans were already angry with Safety and Security Minister
Steve Tshwete for criticizing white women for not taking part in
celebrations on National Women's Day, which commemorates a 1956
women's demonstration against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attending the important rallies, white women were
busy shopping, Tshwete said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still tensions in this society which play themselves
out along the lines of race, and that's not surprising,'' said Tom
Lodge, professor of political science at the University of the
Witwatersrand. ''It's a good thing that they are talked about more
openly than they were four or five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The racism conference, however, may be less effective in
stopping that racism than a strong set of laws against
discrimination, Lodge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
