<HEADLINE> Number of students taking SAT in state increases  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The number of public school students who
sharpened their No. 2 pencils and took the SAT test increased this
year, putting New Jersey in a tie for first in that category.
</P>
<P>
   But the test scores themselves grew only slightly, with both
math and verbal results below national averages, according to
figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey students scored an average of 513 on the math portion
of the test and 498 on the verbal section.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, students averaged 514 in math, a 30-year high,
according to the College Board, which administers the tests. The
verbal score was 505 for the fifth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said she was impressed by the test scores,
and by the fact that averages are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are continuing to close the gap in our average scores
compared with national averages, which is truly impressive, given
that we are also increasing the number and percentage of students
who take the test,'' Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials touted the fact that New Jersey's
average scores have increased since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Math scores increased 15 points over the 498 average posted a
decade ago. Verbal results went from 495 to this year's 498.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like most other states, our main focus in New Jersey is to
increase student performance against our own carefully developed
academic standards,'' state Education Commissioner David Hespe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, I am pleased to see that this year's SAT results
continue a trend of improvement while providing opportunities for
more students to demonstrate that they are ready to continue their
education after high school,'' Hespe said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   According to the College Board, 84 percent of the nation's
colleges use SAT scores as a factor in admitting students.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, 81 percent of public high school graduates took
the test, one point higher than last year according to the state's
Education Department. That ties New Jersey with Connecticut for
first in the country, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hespe said that is an encouraging sign since school officials
know more students would mean lower state averages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yet, each year, they demonstrate their commitment to broad
student participation over selective encouragement of a smaller
group of high achievers,'' Hespe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1834 </TRAILER>
