<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's African Visit Falls Short  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Going into its final leg, President
Clinton's journey to Africa seemed to be the stuff of legacies.
</P>
<P>
   He had secured a place in Africa's heart and history by visiting
twice, and this time he could visit Africa's most populous nation,
Nigeria, which moved from pariah to partner during his time in
office.
</P>
<P>
   But once he left for Tanzania and joined a roomful of African
leaders, Clinton's sojourn took a strange turn.
</P>
<P>
   And by time he left Tuesday, he was empty-handed, without the
full cease-fire for Burundi that would have been a fitting climax
for his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended his four-day trip with a brief visit to Cairo,
seeking Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's help in pursuing a peace
deal between Israel and the Palestinians, another situation
balanced on the edge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I admit, I am an outsider. I admit I have not been here with
you,'' Clinton said in Arusha, where Nelson Mandela has sought to
negotiate an end to ethnic strife in Burundi that has killed
200,000 people in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ''If you let this moment slip away, it will dig
the well of bitterness deeper and pile the mountain of grievances
higher. Someday, when somebody else has to come here and sit at a
table like this, they will have an even harder job than you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burundi peace collapse stood in contrast Clinton's welcome
got in Nigeria. President Olusegun Obasanjo gave him three names,
one from each of Nigeria's tribes. As Clinton left, Obasanjo held
Clinton's hand and walked him to his limousine, even though Clinton
had been vague in responding to Obasanjo's plea for help in easing
Nigeria's debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   He was held in high esteem among workaday Nigerians. After
shaking Clinton's hand in the hardscrabble village of Ushafa,
Evelyn Anieze, 28, said she was impressed that Clinton made a point
to mingle among the poorest, like her.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the slick, muddy roads and chickens scurrying about, she
said, ''We love that he would come here to see this Nigeria, for
this -- this! -- is Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos Shekogaza, 38, a businessman and political organizer in
Ushafa, saw the potential for significant U.S. investment now that
Clinton has visited. To him, significant investment meant a small
factory or a new school.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have lights here now. We have water,'' Shekogaza said.
''Whatever will come, we will accept. A beggar has no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson, Clinton's envoy for democracy in Africa, worried
about that mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some would look at him, because of the gifts of charisma and
spiritual attraction, and see him as a kind of Santa Claus,''
Jackson said. ''He is not a Santa Claus. He is a strategic partner.
With him as a strategic partner, you maintain your dignity and
honor, both of which are non-negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 30-mile drive through pastoral lands into Arusha, tens of
thousands of Tanzanians cheered and waved American and Tanzanian
flags. Those without flags pulled leafy twigs from the trees and
waved them.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Clinton found himself among a hodge podge of African
leaders: Daniel arap Moi of Kenya. Jerry Rawlings of Ghana. Even
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi was represented by his son. Clinton
settled comfortably among them, listening, chin in hand, as Mandela
-- the former political prisoner who became South Africa's first
black president in 1994 and led the country away from apartheid --
chastised Burundi's Hutus and Tutsis for failing to put the lives
of their people ahead of ethnic hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want any part of the world, especially Africa, where
children, women, the disabled, and the aged are slaughtered every
day,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the factions to heed Mandela. ''He's the world's
greatest example of letting things go,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, half of Burundi's Tutsi politicians reluctantly
signed a power-sharing agreement, but more negotiations will be
needed to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, African leaders say Clinton's presence indicated a change
in the way Africa's issues are viewed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has supported our efforts at finding ... African solutions
to African problems,'' Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa said.
''An African proverb says, 'Only the owner can free his home from
mice.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
