<DOCNO> APW20000829.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox, once a symbol of corporate success, struggles to compete  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Xerox, of all things, is going trendy.
</P>
<P>
   The company has just launched the most expensive advertising
campaign in its history using Blue Dog, the popular dog with bright
yellow eyes who has a cultlike following.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Blue Dog - the subject of popular paintings by New
Orleans artist George Rodrigue - is no accident for a company
suffering from an image as a stodgy, Old Economy company that can't
keep up.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of more than $200 million, Xerox is hoping the ads
will help customers realize it makes the latest, high-tech inkjet
printers for the small and home office market, for as little as
$149.
</P>
<P>
   In television commercials that began airing last week, brightly
colored paintings of various small businesses are featured in an
art gallery, with the Blue Dog prominent in each, while an
announcer extolls the virtues of a $149 Xerox printer. ''They're
just a smarter breed of inkjet printer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The company's outdated image is just one of a myriad of problems
at Xerox, a company that was once considered a symbol of corporate
success.
</P>
<P>
   Its copiers were so popular in the 1960s and '70s that the name
''Xerox'' became synonymous with copying, just as the ''Kleenex''
brand became synonymous with tissues.
</P>
<P>
   But Xerox has struggled for more than a year now with slumping
profits, a botched sales force reorganization and a stock price
that has plummeted to one-third of its value a year ago. The stock
closed Monday at $17.12&AMP;frac12;, compared with a high of $50.12&AMP;frac12; a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company announced it would slash 5,200 jobs and
close manufacturing plants to reduce its cost structure so it could
stay competitive with companies such as Hewlett-Packard, Canon and
Ricoh.
</P>
<P>
   The last year was not supposed to be a nightmare for Xerox. In
April 1999, the company made Rick Thoman its chief executive.
Thoman was a former IBM executive credited with helping to engineer
that company's turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman, who had joined Xerox in 1997, had already been
instrumental in the company's push to sell its digital products in
low-end retail outlets such as Staples and Office Max.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Xerox was already struggling to reduce costs as it
shifted from old-style copiers that operate with lenses and lights
to multipurpose digital models that can be upgraded to print, scan
and fax documents when connected to personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also in the midst of cutting 9,000 jobs, or just
under 10 percent of its worldwide work force.
</P>
<P>
   But under Thoman's reign, a massive reorganization of the
company's sales force was clumsily executed and slowed productivity
and sales. The idea was to reorganizing the sales force by
industry, rather than the traditional geographic organization used
by Xerox for years.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman was fired in May, just 13 months after he took the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allaire, who Thoman had replaced as CEO, agreed to come
back on a temporary basis. The company elevated Anne Mulcahy to
President and Chief Operating Officer and made it clear she was
being groomed for the CEO job.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Xerox had to report embarrassing problems at its
Mexican operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company was initially vague about the problems, it
later disclosed that that several senior managers had collaborated
to circumvent Xerox accounting policies. They allegedly created
false product orders to inflate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a $78 million charge against second-quarter
earnings to cover bad debt and unrecorded liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission is now investigating.
Xerox, meanwhile, fired several top Mexican executives, including
the general manager and finance director.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican charge, coupled with a revenue decline for certain
products, helped push second-quarter earnings down 68 percent, to
$145 million, or 19 cents per share, compared with $448 million, or
62 cents per share in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In July, during a conference call with analysts, Xerox
executives were surprisingly candid about the extent of the
company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Allaire warned analysts to lower their expectations for the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And Mulcahy said things had gotten so bad that, ''Xerox people
have lost confidence in management.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a feeling the company has lost its sense of
direction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, she said, employees had grow increasingly frustrated with
the company's slow reaction to its competition, which had clearly
heated up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our issues kept us focused internally instead of on the market
and the competition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulcahy said the reorganization of the sales force is now
complete and the turnover rate for salespeople had dropped
recently. She said the company hoped to keep its strongest
producers through pumped-up salaries and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Both Allaire and Mulcahy declined requests for interviews for
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the company's internal problems are really just
symptoms of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cause of their problems really has to do with the fact
that they're caught between a rock and a hard place,'' said Shebly
Seyrafi, an analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. ''Their core market is
the copier market and that copier market is in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is down in part because many workers prefer to use
printers linked to their computers rather than copying machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the digital copier market, Xerox has been Number One for two
years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the company had 37 percent of the market, followed by
Sharp, at 18 percent, and Canon, at 11 percent, according to
figures provided by IDC, formerly known as International Data
Corp., a market research and consulting company based in
Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But in the total copier market - analog and digital - Canon led
in 1999, with 31 percent, followed by Xerox, 29 percent, and Sharp,
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is in the small and home office market that Xerox really lags
behind its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the inkjet market of multi-function machines -those that can
copy, fax and print all from a computer - Hewlett-Packard is
crushing Xerox and other competitors. H-P had 52 percent of the
market in 1999, compared to only 8 percent for Xerox. Canon came in
second with 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has tried to make inroads in the small and home office
market. In March, the company announced a $2 billion alliance with
Sharp and Fuji Xerox to develop and manufacture inkjet products for
small and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has also formed a partnership with Dell Computers under
which that company will sell Xerox laser printers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Blue Dog advertising campaign is aimed at showing
customers that this one-time maker of old-style copiers now also
makes products for small and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Always faithful to its owner,'' reads a print ad showing Blue
Dog watching over a Xerox inkjet printer.
</P>
<P>
   But will the new campaign work?
</P>
<P>
   ''The market sees them as this purveyor of antiquated or older
technology and the market has moved on. Copying was big in the
'60s; printing has been big for 10 years,'' said Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have praised the company's decision last year to
purchase the color printing division of Tektronix Inc. in a move
that makes Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color
printing market.
</P>
<P>
   But they say it may be a while before Xerox can pull out of its
recent slump.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may be coming out of it, but if they do they are going to
be coming out of their problems in the 2001 time frame, not anytime
this year,'' said Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kmetz, a director at IDC, said Xerox will be able to turn
things around, but not in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're too much of a major player and a dominant provider of
products to just crumble and die,'' Kmetz said. ''I would expect to
see Xerox rally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
