<HEADLINE> SI prosecutor recovering from second kidney transplant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Staten Island District Attorney William Murphy
was recovering Tuesday at a Manhattan hospital after his second
kidney transplant in six months - both with organs donated by
members of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Mount Sinai Medical Center believed Monday's
transplant surgery was successful, said Murphy's spokesman, Marlene
Markoe-Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the five-term district attorney received a kidney
donated by his bodyguard, Detective Daniel Ingellis. In February,
Murphy's chief of investigations, Mario Mattei, had donated a
kidney to his diabetic boss.
</P>
<P>
   That organ was rejected, necessitating the second operation.
Doctors at the hospital were closely monitoring Murphy's condition,
according to Markoe-Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Ingellis, a 26-year police veteran, was expected to fully
recover and continue a normal life with his single kidney. The
married father of two daughters was likely to miss a month of work.
</P>
<P>
   Mattei, a member of Murphy's staff for 17 years, was back on the
job within weeks of his donation.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, 56, discovered last year that he needed a new kidney
after the diabetes began causing kidney failure. The prosecutor had
spent months on a transplant list, a procedure that on average
takes three years.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's wife, Cathy, his two daughters and a brother were
tested to see if they could be donors, but none matched. Recent
breakthroughs in anti-rejection drugs have widened the pool of
donors beyond family members.
</P>
<P>
   To be compatible, the recipient and donor's blood type must
match, along with other factors that show whether the recipient's
antibodies will reject the donor's cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
