<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge throws out Princeton's smoking ban  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A Mercer County judge struck down
Princeton's strict anti-smoking regulations Tuesday, ruling that
its regional health commission did not have authority to enact the
ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Regional Health Commission passed the ban in June.
It would have been the strictest anti-smoking ordinance in the
state, prohibiting lighting up in bars, restaurants and workplaces.
It restricted smoking to homes, cigar shops or outdoors. Violators
faced fines from $100 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-based National Smokers Alliance and three Princeton
bars and restaurants filed a lawsuit challenging the ban June 8.
Superior Court Judge Linda R. Feinberg blocked enforcement of the
ban after a July hearing, and gave attorneys the opportunity to
submit supplemental arguments before making her final decision.
</P>
<P>
   In the 64-page ruling, Feinberg agreed with the alliance's
arguments that the health commission did not have the authority to
enact the ban for fire-safety purposes. The judge also held that
the ordinance is pre-empted by state law.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear, Feinberg said, the state Legislature intended to
comprehensively regulate indoor smoking and to do so exclusively.
She ruled that Princeton's ban conflicts with it.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Lewin, the attorney representing bar owners and the
smoker's alliance, said they were grateful for the decision, which
he called ''painstakingly thorough'' in rejecting the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''In each and every instance (the judge) found the smoking ban
violated state law,'' Lewin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ban was an attempt by the commission to avoid going
through the Legislature to change state law. National Smokers
Alliance Executive Director Eric Schippers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly in this case (the ban) was unlawful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Cayci, the health commission's attorney, argued that each
side had its interpretation of the law, and that municipalities are
entitled to legislate.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know if the commission will appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going try to get a meeting together with (members) next
month,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another attorney representing the health commission and a
coalition of 45 anti-smoking groups said the decision will force
the state Legislature to act on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed the court didn't see it our way,'' said
Robert J. Conroy, special council to New Jersey Breathes. ''This
decision will serve as a beacon, if you will, for the legislature.
I think it's very likely that people want to be able to have dinner
without the presence of a known carcinogen.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said lawmakers will either have to enact a statewide ban
or free municipalities to adopt their own legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said his group will continue to fight efforts by
the National Smokers Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't think any group in Virginia has the right to tell
people in New Jersey what to do,'' Conroy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
