<HEADLINE> Daily News driver delivers baby in Holland Tunnel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Delivering newspapers every morning seems pretty
routine - or so Daily News driver Robert Halberstadt thought.
</P>
<P>
   On his way through the Holland Tunnel to deliver Tuesday's Daily
News, Halberstadt, a trained emergency medical technician, made a
special delivery - a 7-pound, 12-ounce baby boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was definitely not part of the routine,'' Halberstadt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstadt had just picked up the morning papers at the Daily
News printers in Jersey City, N.J. around 4:30 a.m. when he got
stuck in heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed that each time the car in front of him stopped, the
driver got out and went to the passenger side to look in the
window.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you get a sense that something is wrong, so I asked
him and he told me his wife was having a baby,'' Halberstadt
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   After calling 911 on his cellular phone, Halberstadt got out of
his van and went over to the man's car, where he saw that the
mother's water had broke, and the baby's head had crowned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Next thing I know, I'm holding the baby in the middle of the
tunnel, under 50 feet of water,'' Halberstadt said.
</P>
<P>
   After bringing the couple, who asked not to be identified, to an
ambulance at the New York side of the tunnel, Halberstadt continued
on his way to Sheepshead Bay and Brighton Beach to deliver the
morning papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Holland Tunnel baby was the second born in the past two days
in New York's bridge and tunnel network. Another baby was born
Monday morning inside a taxi at a toll plaza on the Triborough
Bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
