<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State reaches 8.1 million, up 5 percent through the 1990s, with Somerset leading the way </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey's population reached 8.14
million last year, up 5 percent over the past decade during a
period when the national population increased about 9 percent to
about 273 million.
</P>
<P>
   The state's population increased by 48,000 from 1998 to 1999, an
increase of about 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These estimates are based on the hard data collected in the 1990
census and revised annually according to surveys and samples, this
for the ninth and last time. By December, the first new numbers are
due from the actual counting in the 2000 census now under way.
</P>
<P>
   The most vigorous growth of the past decade was in Somerset and
Hunterdon counties, where the increasing development of rural areas
brought in 63,000 people. Somerset added 46,700 people, up 19.4
percent, nearly four times the statewide rate. Hunterdon added
16,000 people, up 15.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Similar growth rates in the decade were measured in Sussex,
Monmouth and Ocean counties. Ocean had the largest numerical growth
in the state, adding 63,000 people over nine years, a rise of 14.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This was offset statewide by the decline of 30,000 people in
Essex County, down 3.9 percent from 1990 to 1999. The other major
urban counties lost people as well but in far fewer numbers - 287
in Camden County, down 0.1 percent, and 171 in Hudson County, a
change so small it did not register as a percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Exceeding them both was tiny Salem County, which lost 848 people
since 1990, a decline of 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These decade patterns were roughly true for the population
change measured from 1998 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The one-year change saw population up 2.1 percent in Somerset,
1.8 percent in Hunterdon and 1.5 percent in Ocean. Warren had a
larger growth rate, 1.6 percent, showing that rural area was now
starting to grow at a faster rate compared with earlier in the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   On the downward side, Camden County lost 1,175 people from 1998
to 1999, a marked acceleration in population loss. In Essex, by
comparison, the population loss that had been averaging 3,000 a
year slowed to 967 from 1998 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although popular perception is that the aged population is
growing dramatically in comparison with the rest, this did not
appear to hold in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   There were 1.03 million seniors age 65 and older in 1990,
representing 13.3 percent of the total population. By 1999 there
were 1.11 million seniors, an increase of 78,000, or 7.6 percent.
But the proportion that those seniors represent of the total
population was still close, about 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The group of 18-to-65 year-old wage earners increased only 2.5
percent in the same period, but the group of future wage earners,
ages 5 to 17, increased 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of seniors living to age 85 and older was up sharply,
from 94,000 in 1990 to 133,000 in 1999. But as a proportion of the
population that group's increase was less dramatic, from 1.2
percent in 1990 to 1.6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, there were 550,000 children under age 5 in
1990, about 7.1 percent of the state's total. This dropped by 1999,
but only slightly, to 543,000, about 6.7 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.census.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1851 </TRAILER>
