<DOCNO> APW20000829.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MP3.com executive completes second day on the witness stand  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The chief executive of MP3.com concluded two
days of testimony in a copyright trial Tuesday by insisting that
his company did not believe it was violating copyrights when it
loaded thousands of CDs into its music system.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt we didn't require authorization from the record
companies,'' Michael Robertson said at a trial being heard without
a jury by U.S. District Judge Jed Rakoff.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff already ruled that the San Diego-based Internet music
company violated the copyrights of the nation's major record
companies by offering music online without permission.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the judge is hearing testimony to determine whether
MP3.com willfully violated the copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   If he finds that the company did, MP3.com could be forced in a
worst-case scenario to pay the Universal Music Group several
hundred million dollars in damages. Without willful intent, damages
could be set as low as $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The other four large record companies - Warner Music Group, BMG,
EMI and Sony Music Entertainment - settled with MP3.com prior to
the trial for undisclosed amounts of money and for arrangements for
additional compensation from MP3.com customers.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff said he will decide the matter of willful intent based on
whether he finds MP3.com knew it was infringing on copyrights, and
if it acted recklessly.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he considered his operation a friend of the
record companies, setting up a system that would require customers
to prove they had purchased CDs before they could create an online
catalogue of their personal music collection.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're simply letting people listen to music that they already
have,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1855 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Defense Accuses CIA  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Testimony from a former CIA
double agent was delayed Tuesday in the Lockerbie bombing trial
after defense lawyers alleged that the spy agency may be concealing
evidence on the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Judges ordered Scotland's chief prosecutor to ''use his best
endeavors'' with the CIA to obtain the missing information before
they call the spy -- their star witness -- to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came despite warnings it could impede the trial of
two Libyans charged with planting the bomb Dec. 21, 1988, that
killed 270 people on Pan Am Flight 103 and on the ground in
Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ''The practical effect of granting the request would be a delay
of perhaps a considerable period of time,'' Scotland's chief
prosecutor, Lord Advocate Colin Boyd, told the court.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd suggested the witness, identified as Abdul Majid Giaka, who
was initially scheduled to testify on Aug. 22, may not appear until
next week. Less important witnesses could be heard in the meantime,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has stumbled through procedural glitches since it
began May 3 before a special Scottish court sitting in the
Netherlands. Proceedings are expected to last several more months.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah
allegedly worked with Giaka as Libyan intelligence agents on the
Mediterranean island of Malta.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the bomb that destroyed the New York-bound
airliner was sent from Malta in an unaccompanied suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence that Giaka provided is contained in 25 cables from
CIA handlers who started debriefing him in August 1988, four months
ahead of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Copies were presented as evidence with passages -- as long as an
entire page -- blacked out which the CIA maintained could jeopardize
U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   Although the CIA restored some deletions last week, defense
lawyers Tuesday demanded access to the full texts, arguing that
potentially significant evidence remained concealed.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted references in the cables to dispatches that the
CIA had not handed over.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is plain that what we have is not the full complement of
cables,'' said Al-Megrahi's attorney, Bill Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The judges asked the prosecutor to track down the missing
documents, but they agreed with the prosecution that asking the CIA
to release more of the censored documents would be a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   The judges rejected a defense motion to ask U.S. Attorney
General Janet Reno to appoint a federal judge to look into the
security threat posed by the disclosure in full of Giaka's
dispatches.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts of the newly declassified passages painted a picture of
an opportunist looking to profit from his dealings with the U.S.
intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka, eager to defect from Libya, got the CIA to pay for a
''sham surgery'' on his arm to avoid Libyan military service.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, diminished his usefulness as a mole, a
disappointed debriefer wrote, beginning to suspect that Giaka ''has
never been a true member'' of the Libyan intelligence services.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka also tried to obtain a $30,000 grant in addition to his
$1,000 monthly CIA salary to help him start a car rental business
in Malta.
</P>
<P>
   Debriefers suspected Giaka was taking advantage of his cover job
at Malta's Luqa Airport to engage in ''low-level smuggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Giaka defected to the United States in July 1991, according to
defense lawyers. He is currently in the federal witness protection
program, living under an assumed identity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1902 </TRAILER>
