<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uneasy Calm Prevails in Iranian City  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHORRAMABAD, Iran (AP) -- Riot police dispersed a crowd of youths
Tuesday as an uneasy calm settled over this western Iranian city
following days of violence over a meeting of reformist students.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20,000 people marched earlier in the day in the funeral
procession of a policeman who was killed in riots on Sunday.
Ardeshir Karami was somehow shot during fighting between supporters
of students from Iran's largest student group, who had come to
Khorramabad for their annual conference, and hard-line vigilantes.
Exactly how he was shot remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the funeral, some 400 youths gathered in a
residential neighborhood of the city before scores of riot police
arrived and club-wielding vigilantes sealed off the street. The
purpose of the gathering wasn't clear, but about the anti-riot
police broke it up without incident.
</P>
<P>
   While calm generally prevailed here, anger still flared in spots
of the city, the capital of Lorestan province, whose population of
1 million is seething under poverty and unemployment. The
provincial governor, Noorallah Abedi, suffered a skull fracture
when he was hit with a rock during the policeman's funeral, state
television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Abedi was apparently hit by a hard-liner angry that the Office
for Fostering Unity -- the student group -- was granted permission to
hold its annual conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The vigilantes, like the police, are controlled by hard-liners
in the Iranian establishment. Trouble between the hard-liners and
the reformist students began almost immediately after the
conference began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, vigilantes occupied the airport to prevent two
leading reformists, Abdol-Karim Soroush and Mohsen Kadivar, from
leaving the airfield after they arrived from Tehran to address the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both Mr. Soroush and Kadivar were savagely beaten by members
of the pressure groups,'' Akbar Atri, a main student leader, told
reporters in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of sporadic clashes and attacks on the students
by vigilantes, things came to a head Sunday when supporters of the
students clashed in the street with the vigilantes and the police
officer was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Conference organizers said about 100 participants were injured
in the attacks Sunday by vigilantes, 40 of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   After organizers agreed to end their weeklong conference two
days early to restore calm to the city, their buses were stopped by
vigilantes and security officers in plain clothes who savagely beat
them, Atri said. A bus full of female students was emptied and the
women kicked and beaten, the student group said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Khorramabad conference, held in support of
democratic reforms initiated by President Mohammad Khatami after
his 1997 election, said they had identified Intelligence Ministry
agents and Revolutionary Guards in plainclothes among the
attackers. They accused security forces loyal to the hard-liners of
abetting the vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami seeks to strengthen the rule of law and weaken the
absolute power of the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-liners have closed down 25 publications -- all but one
pro-democracy -- since April. Journalists, intellectuals and writers
who dare to speak out against the absolute power of the clergy are
jailed daily.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown allowed student groups to emerge as powerful
messengers for Khatami in the absence of newspapers. Universities
reopen in about three weeks after the summer recess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
