<HEADLINE> Senate president says patients should sue HMOs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Patients should have the ability to sue
their HMO insurance providers for claims of medical malpractice, a
ranking Republican lawmaker said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, said the
''right to sue'' is a key point in a package of health care bills
he plans to make public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week DiFrancesco announced a $400 million property tax
relief proposal. DiFrancesco has said he is considering a run for
governor when Gov. Christie Whitman leaves office at the end of her
second term.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill sends a strong message and that is the health care
consumer will have a powerful tool to fight back against their HMO
and insurance companies,'' DiFrancesco said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision is to require binding arbitration in disputes
with patients, DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This measure will give patients the right to sue their carrier
and ultimately make health insurance companies more accountable,''
DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also announced similar proposals Tuesday and said she
would introduce her bills when the Legislature returns from its
recess.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco plans to announce his full health care plan at a
news conference in Newark on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
