<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.America Summit To Focus on Economy  </HEADLINE>
By ADALID CABRERA LEMUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Leaders at a South American summit will
discuss ways to boost trade and their economies, but the regional
impact of a U.S.-backed drug war in Colombia will likely be a key
theme.
</P>
<P>
   As 12 heads of state prepared for the two-day summit that begins
Thursday, a foreign ministry official said Tuesday Brazil was
opposed to foreign countries sending troops into Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The summit will start just hours after President Clinton visits
Colombia where he will tour the Caribbean city of Cartagena and
again pledge U.S. support to President Andres Pastrana's anti-drug
plan, known as Plan Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Plan Colombia deserves the full backing of all of the
continent's nations,'' Ivan Cannabrava, a top official at Brazil's
Foreign Ministry said at a news conference. ''But this backing does
not mean support for armed intervention in Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has approved $1.3 billion anti-narcotics aid
package. Most of the aid will be in military hardware and training
and it is aimed at combatting armed groups who protect plantations
producing 90 percent of the world's cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the U.S. aid -- in which 60 combat helicopters will be
sent to Colombia and Green Berets are training Colombian
anti-narcotics soldiers -- say Washington is becoming directly
involved in this South American nation's 36-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. troops, however, are barred from fighting in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Cannabrava said the summit will also deal with ways of
integrating the continent's economies by building a network of
highways and telecommunications systems.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, education and technology are also on the agenda, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ''In convening and hosting the summit, Brazil is definitely
taking an important step toward asserting its leadership in the
region,'' said University of Brasilia political scientist David
Fleischer. ''And it's doing so by spearheading the creation of a
South American-wide trade bloc, which is the main idea behind the
summit.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil alone represents half of South America's population of
337 million and half of its gross domestic product of $1.3
trillion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1924 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State proposes toughening ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - State officials are trying to close what
they see as a loophole in New Jersey's truck ban.
</P>
<P>
   The law currently limits large trucks traveling through the
state to interstate highways. It allows trucks that start or end
their trips in New Jersey to use local roads.
</P>
<P>
   But a fatal truck accident in Lambertville last May has prompted
state officials to clarify the law and toughen the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the driver was hauling garbage from Massachusetts to
Pennsylvania when he lost control of his tractor-trailer on Route
179. The truck hit three vehicles and climbed an embankment before
plowing through the front wall of a video store.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four-year-old store clerk Joan Eschen died. Four others
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the state's ban of large trucks on local roads
didn't apply because the driver left from New Jersey before picking
up the garbage in Massachusetts and returning through the state on
the way to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed changes, the state would consider each part
of the trip separately.
</P>
<P>
   So if a truck is dispatched from New Jersey to pick up a load in
New York and deliver it to Delaware, the driver could no longer use
local roads while traveling through the state.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Department of Transportation Spokesman John
Dourgarian said that was the intent of the original restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a driver's going from one terminal out of state to another
terminal out of state, the driver should be restricted,'' he said.
''We felt the need to clarify it.''
</P>
<P>
   The transportation department has planned two workshops in
October to receive public comment on the proposal. Dourgarian said
the amendments could go into effect by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   American Trucking Associations already has filed a lawsuit
opposing the original ban. A spokesman maintains the ban is
unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's unsafe, unfair and unconstitutional,'' spokesman
Mike Russell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 1929 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia President To Welcome Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana said
Tuesday he will urge President Clinton during his visit to drop
trade barriers to create alternative jobs for the thousands of
Colombians who work in the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrives in Colombia on Wednesday with a high-powered
delegation of U.S. lawmakers, Cabinet members, diplomats and
military brass to speed implementation of a $1.3 billion U.S.
anti-narcotics aid package.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Pastrana lauded the
visit -- the first by a U.S. president since George Bush came in
1990 -- as evidence that ''we are not alone in the fight against
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Clinton's arrival, workers were hurriedly repaving
streets in this walled Spanish-colonial city on the Caribbean and
painting over anti-U.S. graffiti, such as one that read: ''Clinton
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Army troops erected roadblocks on the outskirts and frisked
motorists, part of a massive security operation involving 5,000
Colombian soldiers and police and some 350 U.S. personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist rebels have promised not to disrupt the visit, but some
minor violence and protests have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they found anti-Clinton pamphlets signed by the
rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, outside
three banks damaged by small explosions Tuesday in the western city
of Cali. Nobody was injured in the blasts in the city 470 miles
from Cartagena.
</P>
<P>
   In Medellin, Colombia's second largest city, riot police with
water cannons clashed with ski-masked university students who
burned a bus, chanted anti-Clinton slogans and waved Colombian
flags. Troops and rebels also skirmished with no reported
casualties outside Guayabetal, an Andean mountain town 33 miles
southeast of the capital, Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said he expects the U.S. assistance to continue no
matter who is elected to the White House in November because the
aid plan has both Democratic and Republican support.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana urged the United States also to drop trade barriers
to Colombian products, which would generate employment here and
give Colombians an alternative to narcotics production.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the most important subjects we must discuss
with Bill Clinton,'' Pastrana, appearing relaxed and casually
dressed in a blue sport shirt and tan chinos, told the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit is a political boost for Pastrana, whose
popularity has plummeted here amid disappointing peace talks, a
major recession and ongoing rebel and right-wing paramilitary
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The American aid, most of it in military hardware and training,
is aimed at combatting the armed groups who protect plantations
producing 90 percent of the world's cocaine and a rising share of
its heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the U.S. aid -- in which 60 combat helicopters will be
sent to Colombia and Green Berets are training Colombian
anti-narcotics soldiers -- say Washington is becoming directly
involved in this South American nation's 36-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   Head-to-head clashes between U.S.-backed troops and the rebels
seem inevitable since the FARC makes huge profits by protecting and
taxing drug crops, and has vowed to fight efforts by the troops to
seize drug plantations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. troops are barred from fighting in the war. U.S. officials
scoff at notions the United States is becoming involved in a
Vietnam-like quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said the military aid was welcome but that for a
longer-term solution, Colombian products, especially textiles,
require tariff-free access to U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the farms which produce cocaine and heroin from coca and
poppy plants are owned by subsistence farmers. Itinerant harvesters
who used to pick coffee or cotton were driven out of work when
prices dropped and now pick drug crops, Pastrana noted.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be 618,000 acres of cotton in Colombia, but now
there are only 37,000 acres, forcing cotton-pickers to become
itinerant coca harvesters, Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Colombia gains access to U.S. markets -- either through a
bilateral agreement, inclusion in the North American Free Trade
Agreement which currently encompasses the United States, Canada and
Mexico, or expansion of the Caribbean Basin Initiative -- Colombia's
20 percent unemployment can be dramatically cut, Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can produce cotton, textiles, clothes,'' he said. ''We have
a production chain and can export with very good results. In this
way, commerce can be fundamental in combatting drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, meanwhile, said he was disappointed with the
relatively small contributions pledged from mostly European donors
at a July conference in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is seeking $2.3 billion from Europe and Japan but only
won pledges of some $600 million. While most of the military aid
comes from the United States, the other donors were to have
provided money for alternative crop development and other
nonmilitary assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't get the funds we wanted,'' Pastrana said, adding
that another fund-raising attempt would be made within months.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Clinton for his one-day visit are 11 members of
Congress including House Speaker Dennis Hastert, as well as
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Attorney General Janet Reno,
White House drug czar Barry McCaffrey and Gen. Charles Wilhelm, the
Miami-based chief of U.S. military operations in Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 1933 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder suspect dies in prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Department of Corrections is waiting
for results of an autopsy performed on an inmate who died in a
Trenton facility Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mazzola was found dead in his cell at the Central
Reception and Processing Facility on Monday night. Medical
personnel found him when they arrived to administer medication for
a pre-existing condition, said corrections spokesman Chris Carden.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old from Shamong was charged with the 1999 shooting
death of his father. He was moved from the Burlington County Jail,
where he had been jailed in lieu of $200,000 bail, to Trenton on
Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzola was to be transferred to another state prison to serve
time on an unrelated drug conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington County First Assistant Prosecutor Raymond Milavsky
said Mazzola had been sentenced to three years in state prison on
drug charges stemming from a 1998 arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very unfortunate episode,'' Milavsky told the
Courier-Post of Cherry Hill. ''I was told he died in his sleep, but
I don't know if (Mazzola's) diabetes was a contributing factor. We
have to wait for the autopsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzola's public defender, Edward Lavelle, said there was no
indication of suicide or foul play.
</P>
<P>
   Another Burlington County inmate recently died in custody. The
man died from an apparent suicide Aug. 17 in the county jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
