<DOCNO> APW20000829.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic light camera bill aimed at reducing red-light violations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AMHERST, N.Y. (AP) - Two Buffalo-area men are on a crusade to
stop red-light runners by putting cameras in traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph W. Kolkmeyer and Anthony G. Moeser, a town of Amherst
engineer, have already collected 1,000 signatures and persuaded a
state lawmaker to introduce legislation giving municipalities the
option of installing the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill sponsored by Assemblyman Sam Hoyt, a Buffalo
Democrat, cameras would photograph the rear license plate of the
offender's vehicle. Violators would receive a ticket in the mail.
Lockheed Martin, a manufacturer of the cameras, has offered to pay
upfront costs in return for a percentage of collected fines.
</P>
<P>
   Several concerns, such as funding, privacy, and who gets the
ticket if the owner wasn't driving the vehicle have stalled
efforts, but Hoyt hopes to gain approval for a pilot program by
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Several police officers applaud the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The camera) is there 24 hours a day. We can't be,''
Cheektowaga Lt. Mark E. Nacke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 2006 </TRAILER>
