<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nader Seeks Union's Endorsement  </HEADLINE>
By KRISTEN HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERIE, Pa. (AP) -- Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader
sought the endorsement of an electrical workers' union Tuesday and
said the Democratic Party -- labor's traditional partner in politics
-- promises too much and delivers too little.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the United Electrical, Radio and Machine Workers of
America's annual convention, Nader offered himself as a strong
alternative to Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to protect labor rights, fight for a higher minimum
wage and push for universal health care. And he claimed that
President Clinton and Vice President Gore have failed to push hard
for a ban on hiring permanent replacements for striking workers
despite voicing support for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats have the support of most unions without getting
anything back,'' said Nader, who basked in the cheers and repeated
standing ovations. ''All they get is the phrase, 'You'd better
support us because the Republicans are terrible.'''
</P>
<P>
   The union's 200 delegates were to debate Wednesday whether to
endorse Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Union spokesman Peter Gilmore said the union usually declines to
endorse presidential candidates, and has endorsed only four in its
history -- Franklin Roosevelt, Lyndon Johnson, George McGovern and
Michael Dukakis. A Nader endorsement would be its first departure
from backing Democrats, Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said the main roadblock to a significant Green Party
challenge is ''the feeling in America that we can't win. It takes
pioneers like this union, I hope, to say, 'I'll vote my dreams, not
my fears,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Peniska, a delegate from Alpoint, S.D., said he would
support endorsing Nader, describing him as a viable candidate who
could make an impact in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''He could do a good job for labor people,'' Peniska said.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, meanwhile, a federal judge refused to order
that Nader be put on the state's general election ballot after
failing to file the required number of petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers had argued that the state's June filing deadline
amounted to an unconstitutional restriction on the ability of
third-party candidates to collect those signatures in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 2057 </TRAILER>
