<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Blocks 'Choose Life' Licenses  </HEADLINE>
By BRETT MARTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A federal judge on Tuesday temporarily
blocked Louisiana from issuing anti-abortion ''Choose Life''
license plates, saying lawmakers should not have approved auto tags
that express only one side of a volatile policy debate.
</P>
<P>
   Free speech provisions of the Constitution require license plate
designs to be neutral, said U.S. District Judge Stanwood Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state has chosen license plates as a forum for speech.
Once it makes this choice, it cannot discriminate against another
viewpoint,'' Duval wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is temporary, pending trial. State lawyers were
reviewing it to see if they would appeal or proceed to trial, said
Denise Bottcher, an attorney general's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a victory for the Center for Reproductive Law
and Policy, which filed a lawsuit on behalf of a pair of New
Orleans residents, the National Council of Jewish Women and Rabbi
Robert Loewy.
</P>
<P>
   The plates -- which state ''Choose Life'' and depict a baby,
wrapped in a blanket, carried in the beak of the state bird, a
brown pelican -- would cost motorists $25 in addition to other
registration fees.
</P>
<P>
   A committee that includes members of anti-abortion groups would
recommend how the state should spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed that the women and children of this state
who would have been helped by the money from these plates will see
a delay in getting that money,'' said Kathleen Benfield, a member
of The American Family Association, a Mississippi-based
conservative Christian group that backed the plates.
</P>
<P>
   The only other state with a ''Choose Life'' plate is Florida,
which began selling its version this month despite a pending legal
challenge similar to the Louisiana lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
