<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru prime minister denies government involvement in Berenson decision </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) - President Alberto Fujimori said Tuesday that a
military court was obligated to revoke an American woman's life
prison sentence and grant a civilian trial because of evidence
suggesting she was not a leader of a leftist rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was ''based on new elements'' that indicate Lori
Berenson was not ''a head of a terrorist group but probably a
militant or sympathizer,'' said Fujimori, who had long maintained
that the New York native played a leadership role among the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori declined to elaborate further on the type of new
evidence. But his suggestion points to what could be a critical
element in a new trial in a civilian court because rebel leadership
was a key aspect of her conviction for aggravated terrorism, also
called treason in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that the case has been passed to the civilian court
does not mean she is going to go free,'' Fujimori told reporters.
''The penal code is clear. Terrorism is also punished in the
civilian court. The minimum is 20 years and there are also life
sentences.'' In Peru, sympathy for terrorism is a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The former Massachusetts Institute of Technology student was
found guilty of treason in January 1996 for allegedly helping the
leftist Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement plan an attack on Peru's
Congress. Peruvian authorities say they foiled the alleged plan.
</P>
<P>
   Her imprisonment, often in conditions described as harsh by her
supporters, has been a sore point in U.S.-Peruvian relations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Justice Minister Alberto Bustamante said Berenson,
30, had been transferred early Tuesday from the Socabaya prison in
Peru's southern Andes to an unspecified penitentiary in the
capital, Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson has denied that she helped mastermind the alleged plot
and insists she was never a member of the rebel group, commonly
known by its Spanish acronym, MRTA. But sympathy is not evident
from Peruvians, who were caught in the cross fire of rebel violence
during the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Burned into their memories is the image of Berenson's public
pre-sentence declaration in 1996 in which she angrily screamed
support for Peru's poor and shouted, ''There are no criminal
terrorists in the MRTA. It is a revolutionary movement.'' The
statement was considered by most here to be an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, a legal adviser for
Berenson's family in New York, said a new trial is unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will resist a trial. She's been held now for four years and
nine months and it has been admitted that she was held in error,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Tom Nooter, another family legal adviser, said the new
evidence does not stem from a re-examination of facts surrounding
Berenson's first trial. Instead, he said, the military court tapped
into subsequent investigations of the MRTA rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   ''The arrest of Lori did not end the investigation of the MRTA
at that time,'' Nooter said. ''I believe that further investigation
involving the structure of the MRTA led them to believe that she
was not ever a leader, which was what was required for the military
conviction to stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Clinton administration has urged Peru to grant
Berenson a new trial, arguing that the secret nature of her trial
didn't meet due process standards. Berenson and her supporters have
maintained that she was not allowed to present evidence at her
trial or to question prosecution witnesses before being sentenced
by a hooded judge.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Fujimori had steadfastly sworn Berenson would
serve out her life sentence in a Peruvian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians charged that the surprise decision by the
military court was another example of government manipulation in
Peru's legal system, and accused Fujimori's government of caving in
to international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Federico Salas denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The presumption is that this came from government intervention
in the judiciary,'' Salas told foreign correspondents. ''In the
case of Lori Berenson, nothing more was done than confirm the
actions of those within the country that have powers over judicial
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The central government doesn't meddle in the military or
civilian courts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International pressure has mounted on Fujimori to improve Peru's
damaged democracy since he claimed victory in a May presidential
runoff, amid irregularities and allegations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Besides pushing for reforms to Peru's legal system, the
Organization of American States has also insisted that Fujimori
comply with the rulings of the Inter-American Court of Human
Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
