<HEADLINE> Yanks' Martinez Sits Out Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- New York Yankees first baseman Tino Martinez was
out of the lineup Tuesday night against the Seattle Mariners
because of a hyperextended left foot, sustained while sliding into
home plate Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was available as a pinch-hitter, Yankees manager Joe
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll see how he feels,'' Torre said. ''I think he'll be OK
tomorrow. I hope I shut him down for the night. I hope I don't need
him to pinch hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said his left foot was swollen and sore. He was injured
when his foot hit catcher Dan Wilson's shin guard when he was
thrown out at the plate while trying to score from second base in
the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a little swollen and it's sore a little bit,''
Martinez said. ''I told him (Torre) I could play without any
problems without favoring it. But he decided to give me one day
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a left-handed batter, would have been in the lineup
against left-hander Jamie Moyer of the Mariners if his foot hadn't
been hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had Jorge Posada at first base in Martinez's place.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, who came out of Monday night's game in the eighth
when his left hamstring cramped up, is scheduled to make his next
start Sunday against Minnesota at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Clemens was ''100 percent'' and Clemens said before
Tuesday night's game against Seattle that he felt ''fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens took part in the Yankees' warmup drills, then iced his
left hamstring as a precaution.
</P>
</TEXT>
