<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Perfect Storm' Filmmakers Sued  </HEADLINE>
By THEO EMERY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The family of doomed fishing boat captain Frank
William ''Billy'' Tyne Jr. is suing the makers of this summer's big
screen hit ''The Perfect Storm,'' contending he was depicted in a
''false and unflattering light.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyne's two daughters and his wife filed a lawsuit Thursday in
U.S. District Court in Orlando, Fla., against Time Warner
Entertainment Co. and the two companies that produced the film. The
lawsuit contends that Tyne was cast in a negative light in the
film, that it was produced without their consent and their privacy
was violated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The family felt wronged, and they wanted something done,''
said the family's attorney, Stephen J. Calvacca of Orlando.
''Fiction, as fiction, is protected speech. Fiction, masquerading
as fact, is not protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner released a statement Tuesday saying that the studio
did not need permission from Tyne's family to make the film or
portray him. The studio challenged the claim that Tyne was depicted
in a negative light.
</P>
<P>
   ''We most certainly disagree with the plaintiffs' claim that the
film in any way disparaged Mr. Tyne or tarnished his memory. This
lawsuit implicates fundamental First Amendment freedoms and we
intend therefore to vigorously defend it,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The film, based on the book by the same name by author Sebastian
Junger, tells the story of Tyne's final swordfishing expedition in
October 1991 into the heart of storms that converged in the North
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Tyne and five crew members on the Gloucester-based boat all
drowned, and the boat, the Andrea Gail, was never found.
</P>
<P>
   Junger's book became a best seller, and the movie released this
summer captivated audiences across the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, the film depicted Tyne, who was
portrayed by George Clooney, as ''emotionally aloof, reckless,
excessively risk-taking, self-absorbed, emasculated, despondent,
obsessed and maniacal.''
</P>
<P>
   The family is seeking compensatory and punitive damages, as well
as royalties from the movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 2123 </TRAILER>
