<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Bombing Secrecy Order Upheld  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A 1996 order prohibiting the release of certain
information in the Oklahoma City bombing trials of Timothy McVeigh
and Terry Nichols will remain in effect, a judge ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard P. Matsch issued the ruling after
the federal government asked whether 4-year-old order still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for McVeigh and Nichols last week asked that the order
remain in effect because of pending appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Matsch said it was the ''continuing obligation of
this court to protect the integrity of the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh is on death row after being convicted of murder and
conspiracy in the 1995 bombing of the Oklahoma City federal
building, which killed 168 people. Nichols was convicted of
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy and sentenced to life in
prison without parole. Both men have appealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
