<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Job numbers at former air base inflated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) - The agency in charge of developing the
former Plattsburgh Air Force Base has inflated the number of jobs
created at the site, a newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tuesday's Plattsburgh Press-Republican, Plattsburgh
Airbase Redevelopment Corp. employs about 700 people, not the 1,000
it has been reporting. And at least 161 of these jobs are
part-time.
</P>
<P>
   Presented Monday with the results of a Press-Republican survey
of PARC tenants, CEO Daniel Wieneke said the number of jobs is in
constant flux and that the loss of firms such as AMI, which
assembles high-speed train seats, throws the tally.
</P>
<P>
   AMI left PARC in March to move to larger quarters elsewhere in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Another 30 jobs will leave PARC on Wednesday when Direct Source
leaves for the Clinton County Air Industrial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Downplaying a survey conducted by the newspaper, Douglas said,
''The numbers game is not important. Its still more (civilian jobs)
than there were at the Air Force Base.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that PARC was careful to select firms that promised
relatively high wages. Last week alone, he said, two Canadian firms
were dissuaded from locating at the site because they planned to
offer minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The state, through its Empire State Development agency, helps
fund PARCs salaries, administration, advertising and infrastructure
improvements, budgeting $2.5 million for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our funding is not based on how many jobs they create,'' said
Gregory Caito, Empire States regional director in the North
Country.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the most successful Air Base redevelopments in
the State of New York. Were leaps and bounds ahead of other
bases,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
