<HEADLINE> Another Year in Swissair Probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Investigators said Tuesday they have reconstructed
the front part of a Swissair jetliner but need another year to
complete their study of the 1998 crash that killed all 229 people
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 111 plunged into the Atlantic Ocean off Nova Scotia
during a flight from New York to Geneva on Sept. 2, 1998. Pilots
reported smoke in the cockpit about 53 minutes into the trip, and
the electrical systems began failing about 15 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Transportation Safety Board said Tuesday the
investigation so far had cost $34 million and involved 2 million
pieces of wreckage, some as small as a dollar coin.
</P>
<P>
   The front 33 feet of the MD-11 jetliner have been reconstructed,
and safety board spokesman Jim Harris said the fire that caused the
crash occurred somewhere in the ceiling of that section, just
behind the cockpit wall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking for anything that will tell us where the fire
might have started,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   A final report was expected by the end of next year, according
to Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe insulation around halogen map lights in
the cockpit may have helped spread the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration in March ordered
similar map lights on other MD-11s unplugged and inspected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-29-00 2202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000829.0179 </DOCNO>
