<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressFrederick C. Bock:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Frederick C. Bock, who piloted one of three
aircraft on the mission that dropped an atomic bomb on Nagasaki,
died Friday of cancer. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Bock normally flew the B-29. But during the mission that dropped
the bomb on Aug. 9, 1945, he flew another Superfortress that was
used to measure and photograph the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   He flew 36 combat missions before being selected for the highly
secret 509th Composite Group.
</P>
<P>
   Nagasaki was the backup target for the bomb dubbed ''Fat Man''
after weather obscured the original choice, Kokura. The bombing
came three days after Hiroshima was devastated by the first wartime
use of a nuclear weapon.
Thomas Frost:
</P>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Thomas Frost, a prominent University of
Wisconsin researcher, drowned Tuesday in Lake Superior after saving
his young son from a strong current. He was 50.
</P>
<P>
   Frost was associate director of the university's Center for
Limnology.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, Frost had directed the university's Trout Lake
Station, a research outpost north of Minocqua. From the station, he
conducted a nationally known experiment on Little Rock Lake that
chronicled the effects of acid rain on lake chemistry and biology.
</P>
<P>
   Frost was the program director for the National Science
Foundation's division of environmental biology in Washington from
1997 to 1999, where he helped make funding decisions for
ecology-based research.
Jack Nitzsche:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jack Nitzsche, an Oscar-winning songwriter,
record producer, arranger and studio musician who played keyboard
on some of the Rolling Stones' hits and collaborated with many
other major pop figures of the '60s, died Friday of a heart attack.
He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Nitzsche won the best original song Academy Award for 1982 for
co-writing ''Up Where We Belong'' for the movie ''An Officer and a
Gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Rolling Stones, Nitzsche contributed keyboard parts to
such classics as ''Have You Seen Your Mother, Baby, Standing in the
Shadows?'' ''Play With Fire'' and ''Paint It Black.'' He also wrote
the choral arrangements for ''You Can't Always Get What You Want.''
</P>
<P>
   As an arranger, Nitzsche worked with master record producer Phil
Spector in 1962 on the Crystals' ''He's a Rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   Nitzsche also co-wrote the pop hit ''Needles and Pins'' with
Sonny Bono.
</P>
<P>
   His 1963 instrumental ''The Lonely Surfer'' was one of the few
records in which he received performing credit.
</P>
<P>
   He worked at one time or another with Elvis Presley, Neil Young,
Captain Beefheart, Marianne Faithfull, the Monkees and Doris Day.
</P>
<P>
   His score for 1975's ''One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' brought
him his first Oscar nomination. The song that won him the Oscar
seven years later, ''Up Where We Belong,'' was written with his
wife, folk singer Buffy Sainte-Marie.
Mary T. Reynolds:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mary T. Reynolds, an authority on James Joyce
who wrote scholarly books about the Irish writer, died Friday of
non-Hodgkins lymphoma. She was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, she was known for supporting a landmark
Chinese translation of Joyce's work.
</P>
<P>
   She began her career as a political scientist in the 1940s and
taught at a number of schools, including Hunter, Brooklyn and
Queens colleges in New York City and Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   She published her first book on Joyce in 1964 while working as a
research associate at Yale University and in the 1970s became a
visiting professor in English at Yale, where she remained until
1989 when she moved to Washington.
Peter Swerling:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Peter Swerling, a mathematician who became an
expert in radar and stealth technology, died Friday of cancer. He
was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Swerling was an analyst for 13 years at the Rand Corporation
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   He developed a class of ''fluctuating target'' scattering models
in the 1950s to measure the performance of pulsed radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Swerling wrote the ''Statistical Theory of Target
Detection by Pulsed Radar'' and its principles became a key tool in
the design of practical radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   He also developed target models used for stealth technology,
which helped develop weapons used in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The mathematician may have been inspired by a meeting arranged
by his father, Hollywood screenwriter Jo Swerling. For his 10th
birthday, young Peter Swerling said he wanted to meet Albert
Einstein. His father arranged the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein advised the boy to pursue mathematics and encouraged
him to remember important things, such as baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
