<HEADLINE> French Fishermen Protest Fuel Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Fishermen angered by the rising price of fuel
blocked ports and roads around France on Tuesday, delaying tourists
trying to take the English Channel ferry for hours.
</P>
<P>
   They promised a protest rally in Paris on Thursday, and tried to
draw truck drivers into their movement.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen blocked at least six Atlantic coastal ports in
Normandy and closed a port in Vendee, further south. Tourists
trying to catch ferries across the English Channel at Cherbourg
were blocked for hours in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen in the southern Languedoc-Roussillon region paralyzed
oil refinery depots near Sete and Narbonne, while in Provence
fishermen blocked access to oil terminals at two ports. In
Marseille, they blocked a car-ferry port.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen have been on the offensive for a week, trying to press
the government for further concessions on the price of fuel and
other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers have also protested against rising fuel prices over the
past week.
</P>
</TEXT>
