<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Seize Lobster Traps Off Canada  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURNT CHURCH, New Brunswick (AP) -- For the third time in recent
weeks, federal agents on Tuesday removed hundreds of lobster traps
set by an Indian group in an ongoing dispute over fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
   Two Indian boats trying to deter the 20 federal fisheries
vessels involved in the raid in Miramichi Bay off eastern New
Brunswick were capsized, and two Indians were arrested. One
fisheries officer had minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like something out of a James Bond movie,'' said Chief
Allison Metallic of the Listiguj First Nation, who has been trying
to set up peace talks at the Burnt Church reservation between
Micmac Indians and the government.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Fisheries and Oceans spokesman said the
government had to uphold the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''Law enforcement is never pretty,'' Andre Marc Lanteigne said.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster dispute in Burnt Church concerns the government's
right to regulate Indian fishing versus the Indians right to hunt
and fish by their own rules for a moderate livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries Minister Herb Dhaliwal said in a statement released
after Tuesday's raid that Burnt Church residents were harming
efforts to negotiate a settlement by continuing to fish.
</P>
<P>
   Burnt Church was one of five reservations on Canada's Atlantic
coast that rejected an agreement with the government that set
fishing limits in exchange for financial aid. Twenty-nine other
reservations accepted agreements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
