<HEADLINE> Browns Release Terry Kirby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns released veteran running
back Terry Kirby on Tuesday and signed rookie running back Jamel
White on waivers from the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby, 30 and about to start his eighth NFL season, played in
all 16 games for the expansion Browns last year. He ran for 452
yards on 130 carries, a 3.5-yard average, and he caught 58 passes
for 528 yards, a 9.8-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Until the roster move, it appeared Kirby had survived final
cuts. Kirby, 6-foot-1 and 215 pounds, came into training camp as
the backup to Errict Rhett, but lost that spot to rookie Travis
Prentice.
</P>
<P>
   White, 5-9 and 206 pounds, nearly made the Colts as an undrafted
rookie. He had a 96-yard kickoff return Aug. 24 for the Colts
against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terry Kirby has been a valuable member of this team for the
past year,'' Browns coach Chris Palmer said. ''The acquisition of
Jamel White gave us four running backs, and I felt it would be
difficult to divide the running back role into four parts. For that
reason, we felt we would let Terry pursue other opportunities at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Clark, Browns director of football operations, praised
Kirby for his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lot of young players, and the only way to know if
they can play is to play them,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns also signed five players to their practice squad.
They are tight end Lyle Allamon, wide receiver Bobby Brown,
defensive lineman Jeff Dyra, running back Rahshon Spikes and
linebacker Ryan Taylor. Brown, a three-year starter for Notre Dame,
was an undrafted rookie free agent who was with the Green Bay
Packers during the preseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
