<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drawings of 19th-Century Civil Engineer to be displayed at NYC museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME, N.Y. (AP) - Selections from the Personal Papers of John B.
Jervis housed at the Jervis Library here will be on display at New
York City's Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Entitled ''Art and the Empire City: New York, 1825-1861,'' the
exhibit will run from Sept. 11 through Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Jervis is considered the foremost American civil engineer of the
antebellum era, designing and supervising the construction of the
Croton Aqueduct, New York City's first major water-supply system.
</P>
<P>
   Jervis drew the specifications for the Stourbridge Lion and
America, the first locomotives to run in America. A portion of the
America is preserved at the Smithsonian Institute. He also invented
the bogey truck, which enabled locomotives to negotiate the tighter
curves characteristic of American railways.
</P>
<P>
   He was the supervising engineer for numerous railroad and canal
projects, including the Chenango, Erie enlargement, and Delaware &AMP;
Hudson canal projects; and the Hudson River, and Mohawk &AMP; Hudson
railroads.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career during the construction of the Erie Canal as
assistant to another famous Roman, Benjamin Wright, who is known as
the father of American civil engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Port Jervis in Orange County is named after him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-29-00 2309 </TRAILER>
