<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tropical Storm Closer to Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS CALO MEDINA
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A tropical storm brushed against Taiwan on
Tuesday, dumping heavy rain on the northern part of the island
barely a week after a typhoon killed 14 people and collapsed
hundreds of homes.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, named Prapiroon, caused little damage because its
winds were relatively weak, but officials were on alert for
mudslides and flash floods that frequently follow heavy rainfall on
this mountainous island.
</P>
<P>
   In Miaoli county, downpours triggered a landslide that blocked
traffic on a mountain road, state radio said. Forecasters predicted
that mountainous areas around the capital, Taipei, could record up
to 20 inches of rain by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that were closed on Tuesday in the cities of Ilan and
Keelung would be open on Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical storm becomes a typhoon when its surface wind reaches
74 mph. Prapiroon was packing winds of 62 mph, the Central Weather
Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Prapiroon, which means ''God of Rain'' in Thai, spared areas in
southern Taiwan that were hard hit by Typhoon Bilis last week.
Bilis killed 14 people and destroyed 430 houses. The storm also
caused an estimated $129 million in agricultural damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bilis also hit China, killing at least 19 people before blowing
itself out last week, the official China Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Worst hit was the southeastern province of Fujian, where the
typhoon first made landfall, killing 13 people, causing landslides
and inundating hundreds of thousands of hectares of farmland, the
China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
   In Zhejiang province, just north of Fujian, Bilis' torrential
rains loosened hillsides and caused flooding that blocked six
highways and destroyed more than 3,400 houses, the newspaper said.
It reported that landslides killed six people in Zhejiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
